<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM Instructed to Visit U.S. Prior to Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today instructed Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov to pay a
working visit to the United States in preparation for his meeting
with U.S. President Bill Clinton later this month.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's hour-long talks with Primakov at the president's
country residence outside Moscow focused on the agenda of the
summit, which is scheduled for March 20 in the Finnish capital of
Helsinki, said the presidential news service.
</P>
<P>
The eastward expansion plan of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is expected to be one of the central issues
for discussions at the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Primakov briefed the president on the results of his trip to
Brussels, Oslo, Copenhagen and London last week.
</P>
<P>
Primakov reportedly told Yeltsin that some progresses were made
in discussions on NATO's eastward expansion but Russia and NATO
would have much work to do in a bid to reach an agreement that
would satisfy both sides.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long been opposed to NATO expansion, saying that an
enlarged NATO will pose as a potential threat to its security. But
the Western military alliance says it will go ahead with its plan
despite Russia's objections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
