<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Announces Registration for Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian government announced today
that presidential nominees will start registration from April 21
through 26.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the announcement
was made by Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati in a
nationwide gathering of commanders of the Law Enforcement Forces.
</P>
<P>
So far, four dignities, including three ruling clergymen,
have declared themselves as nominees for the 7th presidential
elections scheduled for May 23.
</P>
<P>
They are Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri, former
minister of culture and Islamic guidance Mohammad Khatami,
former minister of information Mohammad Mohammadi Reyshahri and
deputy head of the judiciary Seyed Reza Zavarei.
</P>
<P>
Observers here regard the 54-year-old parliament speaker as the
would-be front-runner in the presidential race, because he has the
support of Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei and the rightist
camp called the Association of Combatant Clergymen.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said that next president will assume office in August.
</P>
<P>
Since Iran's Constitution bars present President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani from running for a third consecutive term, so the
64-year-old president has to step down from the office.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that Rafsanjani might serve as a deputy leader
or still as No. 2 man in the country after Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Besharati said, "holding the next presidential elections in
full security is one of the main responsibilities of the Law
Enforcement Forces during the next Iranian year," which starts
from March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Besharati pledged that his ministry will give equal treatment
to all the contending candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
