<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland's Population Rises Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Finland had a population of 5.13
million at the end of 1996, or 15,000 more than the previous year,
said a report from the Finnish Population Registration Center
today.
</P>
<P>
On average, each Finnish woman had 1.81 children, and the
Nordic country's birth rate ranked second among the European
Union's 15 member states, after Ireland's 1.87 children per
woman.
</P>
<P>
However, demographic experts believed that despite the
relatively high average birth rate, there was no need to worry
about a sharp increase of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, they noted, the birth rate had actually been
declining, due to the country's economic recession and a rise in
the number of Finnish people who prefer to remain single. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
