<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Firms in EU Distrust Single European Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Small firms in Britain are the most
sceptical about the European Monetary Union (EMU) and most
European ownership-managers believed that there is still some way
to go before the single market benefits are realized, according to
a research survey.
</P>
<P>
The European Business Survey, carried out by Grant Thornton and
Business Strategists, shows that a majority of British business
owners reserved deep doubts over the single European currency, due
to be launched in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Uncertainty about European integration is also reflected in the
survey with more than 60 percent of small business across the
15-nation bloc reckoning the single market has not reduced their
costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
