<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper: CIA Drops over 1,000 Secret Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA) has dropped more than 1,000 informants from its
worldwide payroll in the last two years because the agency has
considered that they were unproductive or had likely been involved
in serious criminal activity or human rights abuses in their based
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported that about 90 percent of the
dismissed secret agents were judged to be poor sources of the type
of information the CIA considers important in the post-Cold War
era.
</P>
<P>
The remainder, numbering more than 100 agents, were sacked
because agency officials concluded they were implicated in major
crimes abroad, such as killings, assassinations, kidnappings or
terrorist acts, and they also provided inadequate intelligence.
</P>
<P>
A disproportionately high number of the informants dropped for
such abuses were employed in Latin America during the 1980s and
early 1990s, but some were employed in the Middle East and Asia,
the Post said.
</P>
<P>
The total number discharged approached one-third of the
informants employed by the CIA, the post quoted the agency
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The dismissals resulted from a year-long review of informants
that began in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under a policy established by former CIA director John Deutch,
CIA officers for the first time must submit annual reports
assessing the quality of their informants.
</P>
<P>
They also are generally barred from recruiting new sources
implicated in human rights abuses or criminal behavior, the Post
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
