<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Envoy in Tehran to Save Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel's special envoy held talks with Iranian authorities here
this afternoon to mend ties after expulsion of ambassadors from
each sides.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources said that Ali Tuygan, Turkish Deputy
Foreign Minister, is expected to deliver a written message from
the Turkish president to his Iranian counterpart Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides did not revealed the content of their
talks between Tuygan and Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Allaeddin
Boroujerdi.
</P>
<P>
Tuygan was quoted by the well-informed sources as saying "We
discussed the latest development between Turkey and Iran and I
have told them our stand toward the bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the discussion will be helpful to the better
understanding of our stance toward Iran," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara-Tehran relations went into trouble Saturday as the
two governments have ordered to kick out each other's envoys
within a week.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry announced that Turkish Ambassador
Osman Koruturk and Consul General Ufuk Ozsancak leave Iran in
a tit-for-tat measure against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish consul general in Iran's northwestern city of
Orumieh was declared by the Iranian authorities as persona
non-grata for his involvement in activities inconsistent with
diplomatic norms.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Ambassador to Ankara Mohammad Reza Baqeri and Consul
General to Istanbul Mohammad Reza Rashedi were expelled from
Turkey last week for their statement made in public about Islam
and fundamentalism. Then came the expulsion order Friday to Saeed
Zare, Iranian Consul general to Erzurum, who was called a persona
non-grata by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA only gave a short and brief
report about today's meeting between the two deputy foreign
ministers in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Turkish special envoy as saying
"relations between Tehran and Ankara have always been of special
significance and supported by the presidents of the two
countries."
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi expressed his welcome to the Turkish envoy and
said that dispatch of a special envoy by the Turkish
government shows the importance attached by Turkish leaders to
their ties with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
"Iran has been following the same policy toward its relations
with Ankara," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Rowhani, secretary of Supreme National Security
Council, today expressed his hope that the two friendly and
brotherly countries of Iran and Turkey would continue their
relations in a cordial and desirable manner.
</P>
<P>
Three local English dailies today also commented on recent
developments in Tehran-Ankara ties, stressing that deterioration
of bilateral relations will serve neither the interests of Turkey
nor Iran.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times said it should be born in mind that Tehran and
Ankara have to maintain their cordial ties, a fact easily
discernible from the history of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The urgency of maintaining cordial bilateral ties calls for
immediate steps on the part of both sides to find out the
reasons for the present unpleasant situation and mend fences as
soon as possible, it said.
</P>
<P>
Iran News said that self-restraint is the most befitting
response from Tehran to what is going on in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Kayhan International said that Tehran, while maintaining its
right to retaliate, should work to cool tempers and avoid
measures that may leave a negative impact on bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
