<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Tariff Regime to Stimulate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The new tariff regime recently
announced by the Zimbabwe government will stimulate innovation
and development in some sectors of the economy, Confederation of
Zimbabwe Industries Chief Economist Farai Zizhou said here today.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a one-day workshop on the new tariff regime,
Zizhou said the new structure offered protective rates of duty to
the electronic, leather, clothing and battery manufacturing
sub-sectors.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regime, finished goods, which in the past have
been invading the Zimbabwean markets, are now subjected to
punitive 40 to 85 percent import duty.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''The protection given to these sub-sectors will
stimulate innovation and development as they aim at improving
their products to satisfy the domestic market.''
</P>
<P>
The move is also expected to create new jobs, especially in
the clothing industry, and lure more foreign investment in the
country. enditem

