<HEADLINE> Indian State Bank Opens Branch in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of India
(SBI) today inaugurated its Johannesburg branch, the first
banking presence from India in South Africa, informed sources
said.
</P>
<P>
With an endowment capital of 67.5 million Rands (15.1 million
U.S. Dollars) in South Africa, the branch will deal primarily
with corporate lending and trade finance, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The bank, managed by Indians, will also employ 15 to 20 South
Africans in keeping with business growth, the South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted the sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
In an inauguration ceremony, SBI Chairman P. G. Kakodkar said
that the decision to set up offices in South Africa was based on
the historical ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The SBI will do its effort to support the development of joint
ventures between India and South Africa, Kakodkar said.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between India and South Africa has registered two
billion Rands (449 million U.S. Dollars), India's Consul General
in Johannesburg Skand Tayal said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Johannesburg branch, the SBI is also planning
to open a sub-branch in Durban, one of the major port cities in east
coast of South Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The SBI, which has a network of over 8,800 branches in India
and 51 overseas offices in 34 countries, is India's largest
commercial banking organization, with a share of almost 30
percent in total banking business in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
