<HEADLINE> Over 25 Americans Killed in Twisters, Thunderstorms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- As many as 27 people were
killed in tornadoes and thunderstorms that swept across Arkansas
and four other states on Saturday, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The twisters and storms also flattened buildings, swept away
mobile homes and flooded whole subdivisions and injured some 200
other people.
</P>
<P>
Among the killed, 20 were in Arkansas and seven in Mississippi,
Kentucky, Tennessee and Ohio. Four others were missing in rising
flood waters in Ohio. Searching for them resumed this morning
after a night suspension on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The tornadoes were so strong that 59 mobile home were destroyed
and five trailers in a park were swept away in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
Federal Emergency Management Agency head James Lee Witt briefed
President Clinton about the disaster. Clinton was very concerned
about the situation.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain, strong wind and downed power lines were reported
across Arkansas and in the Little Rock area. Hundreds of homes
were also damaged and two hospitals were treating 80 people.
</P>
<P>
In Mississippi, a tornado that struck Randolph destroyed four
homes and damaged nearly a dozen other homes and businesses. Four
people were hospitalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
