<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebels Take Refugee Camp, Reject Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel chief Laurent-Desire
Kabila today announced the capture of the refugee camp of
Tingi-Tingi, 250 kilometers southeast of the strategically key
city of Kisangani, and rejected a cease-fire proposal presented by
the United States and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Kabila as saying in Goma
that the Zairean city of Kindu, 400 kilometers south of Kisangani,
had "completely fallen" to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Some 160,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees fled the Tingi-Tingi refugee
camp on Friday after they heard that the rebel forces were
approaching.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said that his forces are now within 23 kilometers of
Kisangani, and said that he had rejected the ceasefire proposal
because he wanted "South Africans and Americans to convince first
those who are opposed to negotiations".
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government has rejected any negotiation with the
rebels until what it called the total withdrawal of foreign troops
from Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Most of the staff of international humanitarian groups withdrew
from Kisangani on Saturday, because they said that all the
refugees had fled their camps nearby amid rumors of imminent
arrival of rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, whose forces have been gaining ground against the
government troops of Zaire since the beginning of the year, said
that "the clique of Kinshasa will profit from an immediate
ceasefire"".
</P>
<P>
He also said the Lubutu, seven kilometers west of Tingi-Tingi,
had been "liberated" from government forces.
</P>
<P>
"The enemy forces of Lubutu, which was the stronghold of the
elite forces of the Zairean army aided by mercenaries, including
Angolans as well as former Rwandan soldiers, were crushed," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
