<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Tries to Prevent Terror Attacks on Israel: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) is still working to prevent terrorist attacks
against Israel despite the current dispute over eastern
Jerusalem, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said today.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai was quoted by the state-run Israel Radio as saying
that the PNA was making "every effort" to check any terrorist
attack in response to Israel's recent decision to build a
settlement in the Har Homa area in southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Despite the anger and strong protests from the Palestinian
side, no widespread violence has erupted in the Palestinian
territories, Mordechai noted.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, Palestinians have been holding demonstrations
against Israel, mostly in a peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai said that, in view of the current brewing
tension, no one could predict what would happen once Israeli
bulldozers were sent to the site to clear the ground for the
construction.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have warned against carrying out of the
Har Homa project. PNA Minister of Jerusalem Affairs Faisal
Husseini said Saturday that if bulldozers were sent to the site,
"it will mean the end of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Israeli security service have also warned about possible
outbreak of Palestinian violence aimed at disrupting the Har Homa
project.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel announced the Har Homa building plan last week,
Palestinians have responded with restraint to the decision
apparently under the order of the PNA leadership.
</P>
<P>
Israeli intelligence analysts attributed the PNA's restraint
mainly to the following two reasons: PNA President Yasser Arafat
feared that violence would affect negatively his ongoing visit to
the United States starting from Monday. Meanwhile, the PNA did
not want to disrupt the expected Israeli further troop
withdrawals from the West Bank expected to begin soon.
</P>
<P>
On its part, the Israeli government has sternly warned the PNA
 against violent response, saying violence would end Israel's
further pullouts. Because Israel has the right to determine the
scope of futher troop withdrawals, this gives it a crucial
leverage in containing the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Israeli President Ezer Weizman expressed the hope
that the current crisis over Har Homa project would pass. He
said it was inconceivable that the peace process between the two
sides, which has come so far, would end on this point.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that Arafat would ask U.S. President
Bill Clinton to exert pressure on Israel to reverse its decision
to build new houses in Har Homa. But it is doubtful that Clinton
would accept Arafat's request except calling for restraint from
both Israeli and Palestinian sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Miss Deadline of Further Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel is not expected to meet
the deadline set in the Hebron agreement for carrying out the
first phase of the further Israeli army redeployment in the West
Bank, Israel Radio reported this evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hebron Agreement signed between Israel and
the Palestinians, the redeployment is scheduled to be completed
by this Friday, while the Israeli government will hold a meeting
to discuss the matter only on this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Nevah told Israel Radio that the
Israeli government "does not want to put off the implementation
of the further troop redeployment."
</P>
<P>
He said the extent will be decided by security considerations
for the Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli civil administration in the West Bank
has halted demolishing Palestinians' illegal houses in Area C,
which is under sole Israeli control, in accordance with the Oslo
accords.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio noted that the decision was aimed at preventing
escalation of tensions in the West Bank, in the wake of the
Israeli government's approval for building a new Jewish
neighborhood in the southern outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Israeli government approved the
controversial plan to build 6,500 Jewish homes, in addition to
construct more housing for the Palestinians in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for what will ultimately be 6,500 units in the
southern Jerusalem neighborhood of Har Homa, of which 2,450 will
be completed in the first three years.
</P>
<P>
In parallel, the government said it would start to build
3,015 units for Palestinians in 10 existing neighborhoods within
the city limits, though it would boost that number to 9,000
units over an unspecified time.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials reacted angrily to the building plan,
saying the Israeli government's decision is a violation of law
and its agreements with the Palestinians, and has put the peace
process in danger.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
called on the U.N. Security Council and the Arab League to help
stop the construction in Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa issue is surely to be stressed in this week's
meeting between U. S. President Bill Clinton and Arafat, who left
for Washington today for an official visit.
</P>
<P>
The United States had expressed its "disappointment" last week
over the Israeli government's decision to go ahead with the
construction of the new Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
