<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, Singapore to Develop Economic Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and Singapore are
expected to sign an investment promotion and protection agreement
to boost the economic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued by Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe and Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, who ended a
three-day official visit to Zimbabwe today, the two leaders welcomed
discussions on the mutual avoidance of double taxation and the mutual
promotion and protection of investments that are scheduled to take
place before the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to promote free trade, new markets and
overseas investments and develop trade and business infrastructure
in order to increase and consolidate economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
As part of efforts to boost economic ties, it was agreed that the
Singapore trade development board would assist Zimbabwe's export
promotion body, Zimtrade, in setting up a ''tradenet'' to speed up
trade enquiries and the processing of exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of trade was envisaged in agricultural, food and mineral
products, manufactured goods and services where Zimbabwe could
benefit from the experience of Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
