<HEADLINE> Jordan' PM Reiterates Opposition to Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Prime Minister Abdul Karim
Kabariti today reiterated Jordan's firm opposition to Israeli
government's decision to build new Jewish settlements in Arab's
East Jerusalem, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti made the remarks when he met with Israeli Knesset
(parliament) member and former foreign minister Ehud Barak, who
arrived here today on a two-day visit for talks with senior
Jordanian officials.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government's decision would have negative
repercussion on the whole Middle East peace process, said
Kabariti.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, together with most other Arab nations, has been
voicing opposition to Israel's settlement policy since its
government made the decision to build new Jewish houses in East
Jerusalem last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government approved the controversial plan to
build 6,500 Jewish housing units in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Jordan's Upper House of Parliament
today issued a statement saying that there will be no promising
future in the Middle East without a just settlement to the
Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
It said that it must be ensured that Arab's Jerusalem be the
future capital of the Palestinian State. The Palestinian people's
aspiration to fulfill their legitimate rights on their national
soil should be respected, the statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
