<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Parties Win German Local Elections in Hesse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite record unemployment, German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) boosted
their share of the votes in local elections in the western German
state of Hesse today but was still left behind the leftist Social
Democratic Party (SPD), the lastest computer projection showed.
</P>
<P>
The CDU won 33.3 percent of the votes, up from 32 percent in
the last local poll in 1993, according to the latest projection of
the German ZDF television network.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, the main opposition in Bonn, led in Hesse with 37.5
percent, up from 36.4 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
But in the hottest race in the banking center Frankfurt, the
CDU appeared to be the clear winner by a share of 36.9 percent of
the votes compared to only 29.5 percent for the SPD, the ZDF said.
</P>
<P>
Germany's small political parties were the big losers of the
Hesse elections.
</P>
<P>
The Greens Party posted only 11 percent, the same result as in
the last election, while the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the
junior partner in Kohl's ruling coalition in Bonn, saw their share
dropping to four percent from 5.1 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The far-right Republicans Party also lost votes, winning 6.2
percent compared with 8.3 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Hesse elections were widely seen as a key test of German
voter sentiment prior to German general elections due to be held
in Autumn 1998. The only next sampling of the electorate's mood
this year will be in September for the statehouse vote in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
Both the CDU and the SPD claimed victory after the first
computer projections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
CDU General Secretary Peter Hintze saw the election results as
"an encourage for the reform policy of Chancellor Helmut Kohl".
</P>
<P>
Hesse's SPD state premier, Hans Eichel, also commented that
"The SPD has consolidated, things are moving forward". 
</P>
</TEXT>
