<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-02 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The first shipment of phosphoric acid produced by a
170 million U.S. dollars Indo-Jordanian joint venture will head
for India in mid-April, two months ahead of schedule, Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment will be worth 3 million dollars, said Babu
Varghese, managing director of the Indo-Jordanian Chemicals
Comapny (IJCC).
</P>
<P>
IJCC is expected to export phosphoric acid worth 90 million
dollars to India in its first full year of operation, Varghese
said.
</P>
<P>
IJCC, located in southern Jordan adjoining the largest
rock-phosphate mining facility in the kingdom, is a joint venture
between India's Southern Petrochemical Industries Corporation
Limited (SPIC) and the Jordanian Phosphate Mines Company.
</P>
<P>
Work began 15 months ago on the plant, which includes a
700-tonne per-day sulphuric acid plant in addition to associated
utilities at Shidiyeh and an acid storage facility at the port of
Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
The company will produce 220,000 tonnes of phosphoric acid
every year and export the entire output to SPIC in India, where it
will be used to manufacture diammonium phosphate, a fertilizer
under heavy demand among Indian farmers.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the world's fifth largest producer and third largest
exporter of rock phosphates.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is Jordan's first major project realized
under its strategy to switch to finished fertilizers rather than
raw rock phosphates as one of its main exports following a change
of trend in the international market since 1990.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The fifth session of the Tunisian-Egyptian high joint
committee ended here today with the signing of several bilateral
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the committee, co-chaired by Tunisian Prime
Minister Hamed Karoui and his Egyptian counterpart Kamal
el-Ganzouri, opened Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed by Karoui and Ganzouri include an
executive program for cooperation in the field of tourism, an
executive program for the promotion of trade exchange and some
other bilateral cooperation accords in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Karoui said that both sides had a constructive dialog during
the session and it had results that are likely to confirm the
already strong ties between Tunisia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri, who arrived here Friday at the head of a delegation
to the session, said that the agreements signed include all
sectors and are likely to enhance integration and partnership
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait will pass a privatization law during the
current National Assembly's four-year legislative term which
started last October, Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and Finance
Minister Nasser Al-Rudhan said here today.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rudhan made the remarks following the inauguration of a
two-day seminar here on legal issues in privatization.
</P>
<P>
He said the privatization has been fully studied by law and
finance experts of the parliament and the government as well,
adding that a blueprint of privatization law had already been
devised.
</P>
<P>
In his inauguration speech, Al-Ruhdan said Kuwaiti
privatization was aimed at increasing citizens' role in national
investments, boosting the private sector and encouraging
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait initiated the privatization program in 1994, so far it
has sold more than 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of shares of
state-owned enterprises to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti government officials have expressed the hope that the
parliament would soon pass a privatization law to help kick off
a plan to shed state involvement in some public utilities and
services during 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, participants will discuss the legal
aspects of privatization of public services and utilities in the
country. They will examine several matters related to the legal
aspects of turning government-run projects to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rudhan said that in recent years, Kuwaiti private sector
began to grow and show eagerness to compete with the government
in taking on gigantic projects.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Around-the-clock access to all Automated Teller
Machines (ATMs) will be provided throughout Jordan in its banks in
the network, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a capital of half a million Jordanian dinars
(about 710,000 U.S. dollars), is the first in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
It took six months to execute the project since the signing of
the agreement last July between Jordan Payment Service Company and
Nomad Software, owners of Cortex Software.
</P>
<P>
The number of Jordanians with credit cards ranges between
70,000 and 100,000 but the number is expected to reach 300,000 in
the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The new service will benefit the millions of tourists rushing
into Jordan every year, as most of them are from Western
countries, usually bearing their own credit cards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
