<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today said
rejuvenation of state-owned enterprises is of great significance
in consolidating the socialist system and accomplishing China's
modernization.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remark when attending a panel discussion of the
Beijing deputies to the Fifth Session of the Eighth National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislative body, as a member
of the delegation. The discussion was related to his government
work report to the current NPC session before making a speech
himself.
</P>
<P>
The premier voiced his opinions on Beijing's economic
development and other relevant issues.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches, NPC deputies from Beijing said the
government work report gave an accurate summary of last year's
achievements and analyzed existing problems realistically.
</P>
<P>
They added that the tasks and objectives set forth in the
report were clearly defined, and the measures to be taken are
practical and feasible.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Li Peng emphasized that efforts should be pooled
to do a good job in conducting reform and effecting the
development of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties faced by some state-owned enterprises are a
concentrated reflection of problems that have accumulated for
decades, he added, and improvement of the enterprises is of great
importance in modernizing China and consolidating its socialist
system.
</P>
<P>
He noted the whole nation has reached consensus that reform of
state-owned enterprises is an urgent, arduous and protracted task,
and experiences have been obtained in the field.
</P>
<P>
"The central authorities have confidence in retooling or
upgrading these state-owned enterprises," the premier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since problems of the state-owned enterprises are resultant
from both external and internal factors, Li pointed out, they
should be resolved in line with specific conditions.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his approval of experiments Beijing has
introduced, which featured the combination of enterprise reform
with the adjusted distribution of capitals, labor, and technology,
and the internal management structure.
</P>
<P>
It is a characteristics of market economy that the superior
enterprises excel whereas the inferior ones are eliminated. In the
course of reform process, there will be always mergers,
restructuring or bankruptcy and, therefore, the reform and
development of the state-owned enterprises is a process of
constant advancement.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Li noted, a well-developed social security system
should also be set up to ensure social stability.
</P>
<P>
He voiced his confidence in the reform of state-owned
enterprises, which is bound to succeed under the planning of the
central authorities.
</P>
<P>
On Beijing's development, Beijing has taken new steps in reform
and opening-up and economic development over recent years, and the
overall situation and the popular feeling are stable, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is the requirement of Beijing's own development to do the
work of the city well, the premier noted, and this is also
significant for nationwide reform, development and stability.
</P>
<P>
As the capital, he added, Beijing is the national political and
cultural center, and a hub for domestic and international
exchanges. Consequently, it should provide normal services for the
Party and government institutions and army headquarters, for
expanding international exchanges, for national education,
scientific, and cultural development, and for facilitating the
work and daily life of the residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
