<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
called for developing an objective, comprehensive and correct
understanding of difficulties being faced by state-owned
enterprises so as to work out effective ways to tackle them.
</P>
<P>
In a group discussion with Shanghai deputies to the National
People's Congress now in session here, Jiang, who is also general
secretary of the Chinese Communist Party and chairman of the
Central Military Commission, said that China's state-owned
economic sector has been growing stronger as a whole since
reform began.
</P>
<P>
"China's state-owned enterprises control the lifeline of
the national economy and play a dominant role in national
economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said much progress has been made in reform of state
enterprises since the 14th Party Congress. Reform measures include
providing priority support for big enterprises while giving small
ones freedom of operation, allowing mergers and bankruptcies,
alleviating enterprises' social burdens, and diverting their
surplus labor, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has provided support for, and cultivated the
birth of, a number of large, strong enterprise groups that have
economic vitality, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Small enterprises have adopted flexible ways of operation and
have kept developing amid competition," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president, however, acknowledged that a
considerable number of state enterprises face difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"This has become an outstanding issue in our economic life," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must pay great attention to, correctly handle, and
earnestly tackle, the problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang analyzed briefly the causes of difficulties faced by
state enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"First of all, state-owned enterprises are not yet adapted to
evolving socialist market economics in terms of operational
mechanism and management system.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, they are structurally irrational. The traditional
industrial structure and the traditional product mix are no longer
suited for the change from a sellers' to a buyers' market.
</P>
<P>
"Thirdly, with the influx of foreign investment and a rapid
rise of township enterprises, competition has become ever
tougher for state-owned enterprises. Repetitive construction of
factories over a long period of time has resulted in a situation
where different areas have the same kind of economic structure,
leading to oversupply of many product lines.
</P>
<P>
"And fourth, owing to historical reasons, state-owned
enterprises suffer from too high a debt burden and shoulder too
heavy social burdens."
</P>
<P>
The fundamental way out for state-owned enterprises is to carry
out reforms, he said, "to develop a new operational mechanism that
is consistent with a socialist market economy."
</P>
<P>
"Efforts must be made to rectify economic order, standardize
market practices, break regional and departmental barriers, and
oppose unlawful competition, so as to gradually establish a
unified, open and orderly market system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his hope that Shanghai would carry work forward
at the behest of Deng Xiaoping, who proposed the opening up of
Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Jiang spoke highly of Shanghai's work in the past year and
called for recognizing its important position and role.
</P>
<P>
As one of the largest cities in China, he said, Shanghai has
developed itself into an economic powerhouse and serves as the
"dragon head" of the Yangtze River Valley.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai should lead the rest of the country in reform,
opening to the outside world, and supporting economic development
in central and western regions of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"At present, Shanghai should concentrate on economic
restructuring," he said. "Efforts should be made to reorganize its
state-owned sector with a strategic point of view. Particular
attention should be paid to bringing forth a number of large
enterprises and enterprise groups that have a competitive
strength."
</P>
<P>
Rong Yiren, Chinese vice president, was also present at the
group meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0047 </DOCNO>
