<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Hopes to Normalize Ties With Iran, Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today said it does not want
to see diplomatic relations with Iran degraded despite the fact
the two countries have expelled each other's top diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press conference, Foreign Ministry Deputy
Spokesman Sermet Atacanli, said Turkey hopes to normalize the
Turkish-Iranian relations when the country is concerned about the
mutual interests and security of the two states.
</P>
<P>
He said "Turkey attaches importance to its relations with
Iran," stressing that Turkey has not made any decision to
downgrade its diplomatic level in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Turkey first requested Iran to withdraw its ambassador to
Tehran Muhammed Reza Baqeri and Consul General in Istanbul
Muhammed Reza Rasheed. It then declared Iranian Consul General in
Erzurum Saeeda Zedeh as "persona non grata" on February 27 and
asked him to leave the country within 48 hours, saying the two
Iranian diplomats had interfered with the internal affairs of
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry Saturday ordered Turkish
Ambassador Osman Koruturk and Consul General in Orumieh Ufuk
Ozsancak to quit Iran in a tit-for-tat measure against the
Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel sent
Foreign Ministry Deputy Undersecretary Ali Tuygan as special envoy
to hand over his written message to Iranian President Akbar
Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Demirel said his country values close relations
with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and Iran should abide by diplomatic norms and
protect each other's security interests, but not to intervene in
other's internal affairs and system, the message said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
