<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Highlight Deng's Ashes Scattered into Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- All Hong Kong-based newspapers
today carried photos and stories about Deng Xiaoping's ashes
having been scattered over the sea.
</P>
<P>
Most of the papers claimed that the scattering of the ashes at
sea manifested Deng's selfless spirit, broad mind and his firm
will for the reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
Many of the newspapers including the Express News and Hong Kong
 Standard presented maps about Deng's ashes scattering with a
big-character caption: some of Deng's ashes will float through the
 Taiwan Straits and to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A feature on the front page of the Express News said that Deng
had wished to see Hong Kong's returning to her motherland before
his death. Now his ashes are likely to drift to the seas around
Hong Kong, thus fulfilling his wishes.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao published a commentary titled "the Hong Kong People
 Always Remember Deng Xiaoping's Kindness," stressing Deng's great
 contributions to the development of Hong Kong and the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that it is Deng Xiaoping's concept and
principle of "One Country, Two Systems," "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" and "high-degree autonomy" that led to the
solution of the Hong Kong question, the signing of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration on the question of Hong Kong, and
the promulgation of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
It said that due to Deng's strategic plan for China's economic
reforms and opening to the outside world, China has witnessed a
sustained and fast growth and in turn, Hong Kong met with great
opportunities in development.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Hong Kong people are now confident in Hong
Kong's future, for the is a strong backing from her motherland.
</P>
<P>
It noted that under the guideline of the set principle of "One
Country, Two Systems" and with the support from the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China with Jiang Zemin at its
core and from the central government, Hong Kong will enter the
21st century with increasing prosperity and stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
