<HEADLINE> Nepali Parliament Opens Winter Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Sher
Bahadur Deuba asked all lawmakers to cooperate with the government
in approving a bill on decentralization when the parliament began
its 11th session today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the lower house today, Deuba said the
decentralization bill, which is expected to give more autonomy to
local administration bodies, will help provide relief to local
people who are still deprived of basic requirements like drinking
water, roads and health service.
</P>
<P>
Deuba's three-party government has decided to postpone the
local elections, which were originally scheduled to conclude by
mid-April, till after the introduction of new decentralization
laws.
</P>
<P>
The government will present the decentralization bill to the
on-going winter session for approval, Deuba said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will also seek a vote of confidence for his
government in the house during the winter session as the
government had been reduced to a minority status by an opposition
challenge last December.
</P>
<P>
Deuba is scheduled to table a motion on the vote of confidence
in the 205-seat lower house when the session resumes on Thursday,
Speaker Ram Chandra Poudyal told the house when he adjourned the
session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
