<HEADLINE> More People in North China Bidding Farewell to Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province in
the Loess Plateau had some success in poverty relief last year,
helping 1.04 million people get adequate food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics at the end of 1996, 1.54 million poor
people, more than 40 percent of the province's total, escaped
poverty since the nationwide anti-poverty project began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The province invested 830 million yuan in poverty-stricken
areas last year, providing clean water for 270,000 people and
electricity to 122 villages, and building 1,500 kilometres of
roads.
</P>
<P>
Education has remarkably improved in mountainous regions, with
all schools in caves being replaced by new buildings.
</P>
<P>
Priority was also given to farmland improvements, spreading the
use of plastic sheeting and developing economic forests in poor
areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year's unprecedented poverty relief measures were the
result of a "number one man project", that is, heads at all
government, including party secretaries and governors, assumed
responsibility for designated townships or villages.
</P>
<P>
Last year more than 21,000 officials were sent to help poor
people and as a result one million peasants received scientific
and technological training. The province's poverty relief
department says that peasants in all its 50 poorest counties had
955 yuan net income per capita in 1996, a 27.7 percent increase
over the previous year, and 437 kilograms of grain, up 38
percent. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
