<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1500 GMT, March 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev Monday fired
Education Minister Murat Zhurinov and Culture Minister Talgat
Mamashev for abusing their power for personal gain when deciding
on the list of students to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France remains committed to a Europe of nations rather
than a federal state of Europe, French Minister for European
Affairs Michel Barnier said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to concerns expressed by British Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind over the emergence of "a federal
super-state" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian security forces arrested 50 spies in West
Azarbaijan province bordering with Turkey in the past 11 months,
an official report said here Monday. Information Ministry's office
in Orumiyeh, capital of the province, said that 50 spies and
members of six espionage networks have been identified and
arrested.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A total of 965 people are confirmed dead and more
than 2,600 wounded following the deadly earthquake which rocked
Ardebil region in northeastern Iran Friday, an official report
said here Monday. The Natural Disasters Headquarters of the
Interior Ministry announced that 36,000 people have sustained
losses in 82 villages in the region.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring six degrees on the Richter scale has been
followed by over 350 aftershocks, the most powerful of which had a
magnitude of 5.5 degrees.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- At least 50 people were killed and over 100
injured Monday in a train crash near the central Pakistani city of
Multan, the Associated Press of Pakistan reported. A rescue
operation has been launched. The cause of the accident was not
immediately known. 
</P>
