<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese Province Makes Progress in Anti-Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- In 1996, Southwest China's Yunnan
Province made substantial progress in its anti-poverty efforts
with the help of 10 state organs, including the Foreign Ministry
and the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the 10 units began their assistance
in the early 90s in response to a call by the central government,
and have provided poverty-stricken areas in the province with
funds, technology and personnel.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials in these state departments lead their
anti-poverty teams to the areas to help them map out development
blueprints. With their help, a large number of professionals have
been introduced to the province from other parts of the
country. In 1996 alone, nearly 200 such persons came, bringing
over 20 major technological items.
</P>
<P>
Last year, these state organs organized more than 190 training
courses and trained more than 5,000 local people. In the same
year, these units put over 70 million yuan in funds into the poor
areas and helped introduce over 94 million yuan from other parts
of the country and foreign countries and international donors.
</P>
<P>
Some local provincial government officials told Xinhua that the
funds, technology, and professional help brought in by the state
departments have been very helpful for the local anti-poverty
efforts, and that in 1995 the province had 6.6 million poor
people, mostly living in remote, mountainous areas, but in 1996,
1.2 million had gotten out of poverty, much more than the annual
average of 500,000 in previous years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
