<HEADLINE> Rain Season Delay Could Deteriorate Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Rain season is expected to be
delayed for a month in most areas in Uganda, and the delay could
deteriorate food situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
S. A. K. Magezi, the Commissioner of the Uganda Meteorology
Department, said rain season will run from April to June this
year, instead of from March to May, the local English daily ''The
New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
The current prolonged dry spells are expected to deteriorate
food situation in the country, especially in the east, which is
experiecing famine now, he said.
</P>
<P>
Valdo Odeke, the Agriculture Officer of Eastern District of
Kumi, said people of eight of the 16 counties of his district are
already starving, adding that many people have one meal a day
while others eat once in two or three days.
</P>
<P>
Ogole Meselamy, the Agriculture Official in charge of
monitoring and evaluation in the district, said bad harvest in
his district was caused first by water logging and then by acute
drought last year.
</P>
<P>
Reports from another eastern Diestrict of Kamuli said efforts
to grow food were frustrated by the drought in recent months. Mosaic
disease devastated cassava and other crops in the area.
</P>
<P>
In another eastern District of Pallisa, local councils began
registering needy families last month for any possible
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the north and the west said famine loomed there
partially due to long drought. enditem


