<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fake Silver Coins Made in China's Soviet Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Soviet Republic set
up 70 years ago made copies of Mexican silver coins to use in
areas under Kuomintang rule, according to a Chinese coin collector.
</P>
<P>
The republic was attempting to break an economic blockade set
up by the Kuomintang, said Li Nianchun, vice-secretary of the
Numismatic Society in Ganzhou in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The republic, set up by the Communist Red Army on Jinggangshan
Mountain in Jiangxi in 1927, invited craftsmen from south China's
Guangdong Province to copy the Mexican silver coins to use them in
Kuomintang ruled areas.
</P>
<P>
To distinguish the fakes from the originals, the Chinese
character "gong" (worker) was cast on them, which, because it was
hard to detect, did not prevent their being used in Kuomintang
controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
In fact, according to coin experts, even banks at that time
accepted the spurious silver coins, if they contained enough
silver. The silver for making the copies was confiscated from
local landlords.
</P>
<P>
Li published his findings recently in an illustrated book on
coins made by the Soviet authorities of the Chinese Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
His book has been received well by experts who say that it
fills a blank in the history of Chinese money.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is a manager of a business group of the Ganzhou Branch
of the People's Bank of China, wrote a total of 400,000 characters
on the subject after 20 years of study on the history of Chinese
money-making.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
