<HEADLINE> Scientists Monitoring Global Air Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Local and overseas scientists
will exchange their views in the study of global and regional air
pollution at a seminar to be opened here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Hosted by the Hong Kong Polytechnic University (PolyU), the
Atmospheric Chemistry Workshop is to study issues such as global
warming and climate change. Some 50 atmospheric scientists from
the United States, Japan, China, Taiwan and Hong Kong will take
part in the four-day academic event.
</P>
<P>
Air quality has become a concern for many Asian cities, where
rapid economic and population growth has led to drastically rising
 emission of air pollutants. That is why one of the main topics at
 the workshop will be on a regional air monitoring project now
being undertaken by the Atmospheric Research Group of the PolyU.
</P>
<P>
A report will be presented on the research results, which will
have
 far-reaching implications for the assessments of climate change,
chemistry and transport of airborne pollutants and urban air
quality in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the United States will report their findings
from an air mission conducted in 1994, when a U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration aircraft was used to
undertake studies on air chemistry over the West Pacific at many
locations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
