<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Expresses Concern Over Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif expressed deep concern over the bomb blast which damaged
the office of a newspaper in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said in an official handout that the blast, which ripped
through the office of the Urdu language newspaper Qaumi Akhbar
early today, amounts to an assault on the freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked the Sindh provincial authorities to
probe into the incident and apprehend the culprits.
</P>
<P>
Two employees of Qaumi Akhbar were slightly injured when a
time-bomb went off at 5:53 a.m. in the newspaper's building in
Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Chief Minister of Sindh province, Liaquat Ali Jatoi, earlier
ordered an inquiry into the bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
The government will take necessary measures for the enforcement
of law and order in Karachi, the Sindh capital and Pakistan's
largest city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Though resulting in minor casualties, the extent of damage
caused by the blast was estimated by the executive editor of the
newspaper, Mukhtar Aqil, at 10 million rupees (250,000 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The newspaper's offices, nearby rooms, newly acquired
computers, air conditioners and other equipment were damaged in
the blast, Aqil was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
No group or people has claimed responsibility so far for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the bomb disposal experts discovered that the
bomb was a home-made device of 400 gram TNT with a timer.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was placed on the first floor and its impact made a 14
inch diameter hole, the sources quoted the bomb experts saying.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, there were no staff in the office when the bomb
ripped through the office, causing major damage to the equipment
in the room, the sources said. The staff usually come to office at
around 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Local police in Karachi are investigating the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
