<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Breakthrough in Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China now ranks second in the
world in term of overall electricity capacity, with a modern power
industry taking shape, according to Shi Dazhen, the minister of
Power Industry.
</P>
<P>
Shi said recently in Shanghai that China generated 1.075
trillion kilowatt hours of electricity last year, and there are
now 12 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions where
electricity is available in every village.
</P>
<P>
China has seen quick growth in its power industry in recent
years, and the tension between supply and demand in power has
eased up, he said. The country will realize the goal of bringing
electricity to 95 percent of its rural families and make it
available in every county by the year 2000, he added.
</P>
<P>
Construction has started on two nuclear power units for the
second stage of the country's Qinshan Nuclear Power Station in
Zhejiang Province, each with a generating capacity of 600,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
China will start issuing bonds for power industry enterprises
to raise funds and will speed up the listing of those enterprises
on the stock market this year, the Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, China has utilized 12 billion US
dollars in foreign investment in its power industry.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that China will focus on clarifying the relationship
between the state power industry and its major subsidiaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
