<HEADLINE> Pak President Expresses Grief Over Train Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari expressed today his deep grief and sorrow over the loss of
lives in a train accident which occurred this morning leaving 125
people dead and about 450 others injured.
</P>
<P>
In his message to the bereaved families, Leghari assured the
injured that the government would provide all possible help for
their recovery.
</P>
<P>
Five cars of a train which was heading for the southern port
city of Karachi skidded off the tracks early today near Khanewal,
southwest of Lahore, the Punjab capital.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif earlier visited the site of the
accident and asked the local government to hold immediate inquiry
into the mishap.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered local hospital authorities and health
departments to ensure provision of the best possible medical
treatment to the injured.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Punjab Province Tariq Rahim also expressed deep
grief and sorrow over the accident.
</P>
<P>
As the rescue operations are still going on, the death toll is
likely to exceed 150 as some parts of the cars were still buried
in sand.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the tragedy has not been found so far, but some
reports suggested that some problem in the brake system of the
train may have directly led to the derailment.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated train reportedly developed some problem in the
brake system just before approaching the Mirshah station near
Khanewal, making the driver unable to stop the train, sources at
the Khanewal station were quoted as saying.  
</P>
