<HEADLINE> German Scientist Receives Chinese Science Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's top science administrative
office today held a special award ceremony - for just one German
scientist.
</P>
<P>
Uli Schwarz, 63, was given the 1996 China International Science
and Technology Cooperation Award from the State Council for his
efforts in establishing China's first biochemical research lab.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Science and Technology Commission
(SSTC) said that the award is intended for foreign organizations,
scientists, engineers, and administrators who contribute to
Sino-foreign scientific and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, SSTC's vice minister, said that Professor Schwarz
blazed new trails in helping Chinese scientists in Shanghai set up
a lab affiliated to the Max Planck Laboratory in Germany.
</P>
<P>
After years of efforts, the lab and the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) formed a group of nearly 100 Chinese scientists and
doctors as future academic leaders in biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
His lab in the Shanghai Institute of Cell Biology, attached to
CAS, has provided opportunities for academic exchanges between
Chinese scientists and their international counterparts since
April 1985.
</P>
<P>
Schwarz, who is executive director of the Biochemistry
Laboratory of the Max Planck Lab, invited more than 60 well-known
scientists from Germany and European countries to lecture in China.
</P>
<P>
Three other scientists on the 1996 winners' list are the
Chinese-American physicist Samuel C.C. Ting, aerodynamics expert
G.S. Bisigensi from the former Soviet Union, and the
Chinese-American architect I.M.Pei.  
</P>
</TEXT>
