<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators Concerned About Urban Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- While giving high credit to
government achievement in poverty relief in the countryside,
Chinese legislators today voiced their concern about an increasing
number of urban residents in China falling into economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
As China deepens enterprise reforms, some workers have been
displaced, and this, coupled with the failure of service
industries to create enough job opportunities, has landed some of
them in economic difficulties, said deputies to the Eight National
People's Congress (NPC), which has been in session since last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Guangguo, an NPC deputy and secretary of Wanxian Municipal
Party Committee in Sichuan Province, said that the number of
people living below the poverty line in rural areas of Wanxian has
come down to 920,000 from 2.9 million and that it will not be a
problem to eliminate rural poverty by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
"But, what worries me is that the number of urban poor is
increasing as more workers are displaced," Chen said, pledging to
put urban poverty relief on the local government's work agenda.
</P>
<P>
"We should not bring the issue of urban poverty into the 21st
century," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In response to the concern of the deputies, Doj Cering,
Minister of Civil Affairs, said the central government has already
begun paying attention to poverty relief in cities while doing a
great deal to eliminate destitution in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The central government has built "three defense lines" for
reducing urban poverty, namely, establishing an unemployment
insurance fund, stipulating a minimum wage, and establishing a
system that ensures a minimum standard of living in urban areas,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng said earlier this week in his
government work report, "We must take care of employees, including
retired ones, of enterprises which have completely or partially
suspended production, helping them overcome livelihood-related
difficulties."
</P>
<P>
Zhao Chunmei, a worker of Chongqing No. 2 Textile Mill, said
many of her fellow workers are living on a subsistence monthly
wage of 120 yuan (about 15 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
There are some other factories like the textile mill in
Chongqing and other large industrial cities.
</P>
<P>
To resolve urban poverty, there must be a combination of
"outside help" and "internal effort," Zhao said, adding that
Chinese workers need to update their ideas and work in whatever
sectors that offer jobs.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing city government has eased restrictions on
business starts to encourage more poor urban residents to make a
living on their own, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Doj Cering said that more than two million people in 137 cities
nationwide have been covered by the minimum standard
of living system.
</P>
<P>
"For an ultimate solution to the problem of urban poverty, we
must rely on economic development and re-employment programs," the
minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
