<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Minister On Sino-US Joint Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- At a seminar in Beijing this
afternoon to mark the 25th anniversary of the Sino-US Shanghai
Joint Communique, Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
said that Sino-US relations can make further progress, so long as
the principles of the three Sino-US joint communiques are observed.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that 25 years ago, Chairman Mao Zedong, Premier Zhou
Enlai, and President Nixon, with courage and vision as statesmen,
opened the door for Sino-US relations and the Sino-US Shanghai
Joint Communique stands as the first milestone on the road to
normalization of China-US relations.
</P>
<P>
"The communique provides the fundamental guiding principles for
Sino-US relations, namely, that countries, regardless of their
social systems, should handle their relations on the basis of the
principles of respect for the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of all states, non-aggression against other states,
non-interference in the internal affairs of other states, equality
and mutual benefits, and peaceful coexistence," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The US side acknowledges that there is only one China, and that
Taiwan is a part of China, Qian said, and that these principles
have been reaffirmed in the joint communique on the establishment
of diplomatic relations and in the August 17 communique between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"In the past 25 years, under the guidance of these principles,
Sino-US relations have as a whole continued to improve, despite
twists and turns," he said, and "the development of Sino-US
relations has brought tangible benefits to the Chinese and
American people and has helped promote peace, stability, and
prosperity in the Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
History has proven yet again the great vitality of the three
Sino-US joint communiques, which can stand the test of time. And
as long as the principles enshrined in them are observed, Qian
pointed out, the Sino-US relations will move forward.
</P>
<P>
emphasizing that, as permanent members of the UN Security
Council and major nuclear powers, China and the US have important
responsibilities in safeguarding global and regional peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The development of mutually-beneficial cooperation and trade
between China, the biggest developing country in the world, and
the US, the biggest developed country, not only serves the
economic interests of the two countries, but also contributes to
the prosperity of the region and the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, under the new circumstances," he said, "the need
for pushing forward the Sino-US relations is increasing instead of
decreasing, and the potential for strengthening cooperation
between the two countries in various fields is expanding instead
of shrinking."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the key to steady development of Sino-US
relations is properly handling the question of Taiwan. This
question is related to China's sovereignty, territorial integrity
and reunification, and it touches the national sentiments of the
1.2 billion Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The three Sino-US joint communiques have set the guiding
principles in handling the Taiwan question, he noted, saying that
we hope this principle will be strictly observed so that this
question will not become an obstacle to the development of Sino-US
relations.
</P>
<P>
A delegation led by Barber Conable Jr, chairman of the National
Committee on US-China Relations, and Robert McNamara, former US
defense secretary, attended the seminar, which was sponsored by
the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
In speaking of the historical contribution of the Sino-US
Shanghai joint communique, Conable said that the 25 years have
seen remarkable progress in Sino-US relations, and that the
communique laid a solid foundation for US-China relations.
</P>
<P>
The seminar's purpose is to help secure bilateral ties and to
mark the historical event 25 year ago, and also to advance the the
bilateral relations, Conable said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria, EU to Start Talks on Association Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Algeria and the European Union
(EU) will begin talks on Tuesday in Brussels on the signing of an
association accord which will cover political, economic and
cultural cooperation, said Algerian officials today.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven countries of Europe and the Mediterranean region
signed a declaration in Barcelona, Spain, in November 1995,
calling for building relations of partnership among them.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahya said at a cabinet meeting
held on Sunday that Algeria wishes to establish a partnership with
EU on the basis of mutual respect in political dialogue, mutual
benefit in economic cooperation, and closer relations between the
people and cultures of the region.
</P>
<P>
Algerian officials have rejected accusation by some EU
institutions of human rights violations and said that Algeria has
to take some measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 people have been killed since 1992 when Algeria was
plunged in a war between the country's Islamic militants and
military-backed government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
