<HEADLINE> Renault Chief to Go to Belgium to Talk on Plant Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Louis Schweitzer, the president of
the Renault auto group, will go to Vilvoorde, Belgium, to meet
with the local enterprise council members who are angry at the
decision by Renault to close the plant in Vilvoorde.
</P>
<P>
But the date of such a meeting with representatives of the
staff of the Vilvoorde plant remains undecided, said Renault today.
</P>
<P>
Renault announced last Friday that it will close in July the
Vilvoorde plant, its oldest overseas workshop, in a restructuring
program aimed at cutting heavy deficits and strengthen competition.
</P>
<P>
The closure will result in the mass lay-off of 3,100 local
workers.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted a unionist of Vilvoorde
as saying that Schweitzer will meet with representatives of the
Renault Industrie Belgique on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government is angry at Renault's decision and is
trying to prevent it from closing the plant.
</P>
<P>
Schweitzer reaffirmed his decision last Saturday in Brussels to
close the Vilvoorde plant, which was established in 1925. 
</P>
</TEXT>
