<HEADLINE>   Palestinians Hold General Strike Against Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinians in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip are holding a one-day general strike
today in protest against an Israeli government's decision to build
a new Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As called by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), all
stores and places of business are closed throughout the
Palestinian autonomous areas, as well as in East Jerusalem,
Palestinian Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Israeli government approved the
controversial plan to build 6,500 Jewish homes, in addition to
construct more housing for the Palestinians in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for what will ultimately be 6,500 units in
the southern Jerusalem neighborhood of Har Homa (Jabal Abu
Ghneim), of which 2,450 will be completed in the first three
years.
</P>
<P>
In parallel, the government said it would start to build
3,015 units for Palestinians in 10 existing neighborhoods within
the city limits, though it would boost that number to 9,000
units over an unspecified time.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials reacted angrily to the building plan,
saying the Israeli government's decision is a violation of law
and its agreements with the Palestinians, and has put the
peace process in danger.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat called on the U.N. Security
Council and the Arab League to help stop the construction in
Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa issue is surely to be stressed in this
week's meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Arafat, who arrived in Washington earlier today for an
official visit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had expressed its "disappointment" last week over the
Israeli government's decision to go ahead with the construction
of the new Jewish neighborhood in Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
