<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 965 in Quake in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 965 people are
confirmed dead and more than 2,600 wounded following the
deadly earthquake which rocked Ardebil region in northeastern Iran
Friday, an official report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Disasters Headquarters of the Interior Ministry
announced that 36,000 people have sustained losses in 82
villages in the region.
</P>
<P>
The quake measuring six degrees on the Richter scale has
been followed by over 350 aftershocks, the most powerful of
which had a magnitude of 5.5 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The report said that rescue operation is continuing and more
than 8,700 tents, 21,800 blankets, 15,300 heaters and lanterns,
50 kilograms of dates, 2,000 cans and 80 tons of bread have been
distributed among the quake victims.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has decided to earmark 3 billion
rials about (650,000 U.S. dollars) for the quake-hit people of
Ardebil province as part of relief operations.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, Britain, Japan as well as some international
relief organizations have voiced readiness to help the victims.
</P>
<P>
The quake hit cities of Ardebil and Meshkin Shahr and their
surrounding villages, about 600 kilometers northwest of Tehran at
16:31 hours local time (13:01 GMT) Friday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second major earthquake within a month. On
February 4, the quake measuring 6.1 degrees on the Richter scale
jolted northern Khorasan province, killing a total of 86 people
and injuring hundreds others.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 100 village suffered varying degrees of
destruction, some totally razed. Over 11,000 houses were damaged,
forcing thousands to become homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
