<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches Family Economic Advancement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will today launch a family
economic advancement program to promote rural development
through the advancement of the economy of individual families.
</P>
<P>
The first lady, Maryam Abacha, is expected to unfold the
blue-print of the program at the International Conference Center
in capital Abuja today.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha
announced the program in his 1997 budget speech and earmarked 4.3
billion Naira (about 54 million U.S. Dollars) for the
implementation of the program this year.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the money will be used as soft revolving
loans and advances to cooperative societies at ward levels for
the establishment of cottage industries.
</P>
<P>
The program will be led by the first lady as the third phase
of the three-year-old Family Support Program which has been
fairly successful in the areas of health, education and welfare
for the disabled, women and children.
</P>
<P>
The relative government will also be involved in the program.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the official "New Nigerian" newspaper, Professor
David Iornem, Director-General of the Institute of Management
Consultants in Kaduna, said the focus of the new program is
unique and will help realize the country's objective of rural
industrialization, as a lot of businesses in Nigeria are
family-based. 
</P>
</TEXT>
