<HEADLINE> Japanese PM's Envoy to Visit Damascus After Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A top advisor to Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, announced here this afternoon that he
will visit Damascus after talks in Beirut on the "Red Army" case.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshi Hirabyashi, the Japanese envoy, announced that the
identities of some Japanese citizens detained by the Lebanese
authorities half a month ago will be made public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hirabyashi, the Japanese prime minister's advisor for foreign
relations, made the announcements at the end of a meeting with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz at the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He described the 40-minute talks with the Lebanese foreign
minister as "fruitful," noting that the talks dealt with
bilateral relations and the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The case of the "Red Army" was figured high during the meeting,
Hirabyashi told reporters, noting that the two sides agreed that
this case should be handled "in a suitable and positive way in
which the two countries' laws are respected."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official clarified that the Lebanese government
has decided to "very positively cope with this issue."
</P>
<P>
He added that he was waiting for the last results of
the investigations by the Lebanese and Japanese judicial
authorities to distinguish the identities of those arrested in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hirabyashi announced that he will visit Damascus and have
talks with Syrian officials on bilateral relations, the Middle
East peace process and "probably the issue of the detainees in
Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
Syria, with some 35,000 troops deployed on most of the
Lebanon's land, often plays a major role in settling problems
in this country.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese official, who arrived in Beirut last night,
conveyed to the Lebanese prime minister a letter from
Hashimoto pertaining to the Japanese citizens detained
in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Hirabyashi was carrying evidences,
including fingerprint analysis, to prove that some of the
Japanese arrested by the Lebanese authorities are members of
the "Red Army."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese officials denied last week that the security forces
had taken any members of the Japanese "Red Army" into
custody.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Lebanese authorities detained
seven members of the "Red Army" in a search-and-arrest campaign
in the capital on February 15.
</P>
<P>
The radical Japanese group is accused of responsibility for a
series of bloody terror attacks in the Middle East and elsewhere
in the 1970s and 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
