<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reports Flight of Foreign Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors in Nigeria are
repatriating large sums of money home following the removal of
certain restrictions on foreign exchanges by the government.
</P>
<P>
Today's "Vanguard", a major Nigerian newspaper, reported that
the flight of capital has created increasing demands at the
country's Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market since January 20.
</P>
<P>
When the Central Bank of Nigeria intervened in the market for
the first time in 1997, the demand was only 76,000 U.S. Dollars,
but later it soared all the way to 90.4 million U.S. Dollars,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Financial Minister Anthony Ani announced in the government's
1997 budget the lift of the original limitation of personal
traveling allowance to a maximum of 500 U.S. Dollars every adult
and business traveling allowance to 5,000 U.S. Dollars per year
for each company.
</P>
<P>
He also announced the removal of the limitation of home
remittances by foreign nationals.
</P>
<P>
The report said there has been a significant rise in the
number of applications for personal and business traveling
allowances since the budget was announced.
</P>
<P>
It called the removal of the restrictions a major loophole in
the 1997 budget and expressed the worry over the flight of
foreign capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
