<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Arrests 50 Spies in Northwest Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian security forces arrested
50 spies in West Azarbaijan province bordering with Turkey in
the past 11 months, an official report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Information Ministry's office in Orumiyeh, capital of the
province, said that 50 spies and members of six espionage
networks have been identified and arrested.
</P>
<P>
The office said that those arrested had put confidential
and classified information of government organizations at the
disposal of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
They have also taken pictures from sensitive and military areas
and collected information on these places. The spies have
confessed to their crimes and been tried at court, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the office did not point their finger to specific
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
"Propagation of western culture" is among the charges brought
against the group of spies, according to the office.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Iranian security authorities
indirectly referred to neighboring Turkey shortly after the
Tehran government expelled Turkish Ambassador Osman Koruturk and
Consul General Ufuk Ozsancak Saturday in a tit-for-tat measure
against the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in the past seven years for the
two countries to expel their top diplomats each other.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Ambassador to Ankara Mohammad Reza Baqeri and Consul
General to Istanbul Mohammad Reza Rashedi were expelled from
Turkey last week for their statement about Islam and
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the spies, some 10 other people have been
arrested by the Information Ministry in Orumiyeh for being
"agents of the western cultural assaults."
</P>
<P>
The group was said to have been involved in distributing
5,000 pieces of indecent photographs in the province. Some 10
satellite dishes were confiscated from the group as well.
</P>
<P>
Sharing a long border with Turkey, West Azarbaijan province
has consistently had such serious problems as espionage,
unlawful ownership of weapons and smuggling of narcotics and
other contraband items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Committed to Europe of Nations, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- France remains committed to a Europe
of nations rather than a federal state of Europe, French Minister
for European Affairs Michel Barnier said today.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to concerns expressed by British Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind over the emergence of "a federal
super-state" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"It is for us a community of nations, that is to say much less
than a confederation, but much more than a simple partnership,"
Barnier was quoted as saying by today's Le Figaro newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He said this community implies that "these nations are ready to
put some elements of their sovereignty in common in order to be
collectively stronger."
</P>
<P>
Rifkind, who will visit Paris today, said last week in Bonn
that the more one moves toward integration, the more one returns
to the Europe of the past.
</P>
<P>
Barnier said that like France and Germany, Britain should
become one of the great motors for the construction of a Europe of
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"In this respect, the Intergovernmental Conference (of European
Union countries) is a historic chance," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Intergovernmental Conference is now studying the reform of
European Union's institutions before taking in new member
countries from central and eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
