<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Only 19 Rally Cars Start Final Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Only 19 of the original 51 Safari
Rally cars have survived to start the final leg Monday morning,
and the factory teams have been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
Britain Colin McRae took his Subaru Impreza and a six-minute
lead into the first section, ahead of compatriot Richard Burns in
the lone Ralliart Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
Both Cars are reported fully fit after extensive service at the
end of the second day of the three-day Safari Rally, round three
of the World Rally Championships.
</P>
<P>
Local driver Ian Duncan, in the Toyota Team Kenya Celica, is
only two minutes further behind and has been right on the pace
throughout the event despite off-spec suspension from the the end
of the second leg.
</P>
<P>
The only other main team car still running is the Ford Escort
of Armin Schwarz, who was with a deficit of more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
Prederic Dor (Subaru) and Emmanuel Katto (Toyota) have a
three-day tussle to sort out to see who will be runner-up in that
category.
</P>
<P>
Johnney Hellier in a Subaru has only to avoid disasters to take
the GP N honors with a lead of nearly an hour over the GP N
Daewoo Clelo of Azar Anwar.
</P>
<P>
Anwar has the considerable consolation of leading the 2-litre
Cup class, and as the only survivor of the four-car Daewoo team
his priority will be to maintain that position.
</P>
<P>
Although only 19 cars started the third leg, there are still 12
different nationalities in the cockpits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
