<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes Japan for Following US Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official today
criticized Japan for following U.S. policy in postponing the
implementation of the Iraqi-U.N. "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held at the Trade Ministry, Trade
Minister Mohammed Mehdi Salsh said the Japanese government has
been used by the U.S. in obstructing the approval of contracts
submitted to the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. uses Japan, with a representative in the sanctions
committee, to hold the contracts", said the minister, adding
that this is a means of the U.S. to delay the implementation of
the "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Japanese companies will pay for the
pro-U.S. policy, Salsh said: "The Japanese government has damaged
 the reputation of Japanese companies. There will be no
potentials for them to find commercial chances in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Iraq to criticize Japan publicly
since the implementation of the deal signed between Iraq and the
U.N. last May.
</P>
<P>
Salsh also accused the U.S. and Britain of deliberately making
obstacles for the implementation of the deal.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Iraq has submitted to the
U.N. Sanctions Committee 222 contracts up till now, but only
nine of them have been approved.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to finance its purchase
for food and medicine badly needed in Iraq because of the over
six-year-long sanctions imposed on Iraq by the U.N. Security
Council following Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
