<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Outlines New Agenda For Oceans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard today outlined a new agenda for the nation's oceans,
promoting exploitation of resources but also pledging new marine
reserves and some areas to be dedicated to conservation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at parliament, Howard announced 106 million Australian
dollars (81.62 million US dollars) of funding for a series of
programs dealing with marine and coastal management.
</P>
<P>
These include a program to improve co-ordination of planning
for the nation's coastal and marine zones, a key recommendation of
a 1993 Resource Assessment Commission coastal zone inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The government will also fund a project to examine the
feasibility of using satellites to monitor fishing in Australia's
waters in a bid to crack down on illegal fishing, particularly in
the far Southern Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Industries related to the country's ocean resources are worth
around 30 billion Australian dollars (23.1 billion US dollars) a
year, including the offshore oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that the offshore oil and gas industry needed
sufficient freedom to invest, particularly as Australia would
become increasingly dependent on domestic supplies in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that exploitation of resources had to be
responsible, otherwise both the environment and future job
opportunities would be damaged.
</P>
<P>
Howard released a consultation paper designed to promote public
debate, and will release a detailed options paper mid-year with
the aim of finalizing a national oceans policy in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
