<HEADLINE> Moderate Earthquakes Hit Japanese Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A series of moderate earthquakes
struck a popular resort on the south coast of Japan today, but no
damage or injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,000 tremors were recorded between 12.30 a.m. local
time (15:30 GMT Sunday) to 5.30 p.m. (08:30 GMT), but only about
19 were actually felt, the Central Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The strengths ranged from three to 4.2 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
The tremors were centered off the east coast of the Izu
Peninsula, a traditional resort known for its beautiful scenery,
100 kilometers southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Some earthquakes were felt in Shizuoka prefecture on the
peninsula, but no damage or injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
Another series of tremors hit the peninsula in October, 1996,
when 5,978 tremors were recorded and 432 were felt by humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
