<HEADLINE> Philippines' Exports to South Asia Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' total exports to
India, Pakistan and Bangladesh reached 57.074 million US dollars
last year, an increase of 61.75 percent from 35.284 US dollars in
1995, Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the country's Department of Trade and Industry
showed that merchandise exports to India alone swelled by a hefty
80.76 percent as receipts amounted to 36.563 million US dollars
last year from the 1995 figure of 20.228 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among products exported to India are cabled yarn of uncombed
fibers, gloves and mittens of leather, textile spinning machines,
electronic integrated circuits, finished electronic machinery,
coconut acid oils, copper waste and scrap, and prawn feeds.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Pakistan, on the other hand, soared 146.47 percent
to 17.825 million US dollars from 9.778 million US dollars in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, dollar receipts from Bangladesh suffered a decline
of 49.13 percent as total exports amounted to only 2.684 million
US dollars in 1996 from 5.277 million US dollars reported for
1995.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista was quoted as
saying that President Ramos' visit to the three South Asian
countries will boost trade and investment between the Philippines
and the three countries.
</P>
<P>
He said before accompanying Ramos to the three countries that
the Philippine government will give priority to push expansion
into potentially big markets in South Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
