<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Train Accident Rises to 125 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the train
accident, which occurred this morning in central Pakistan, rose to
125 while the number of the injured stood at 450, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
Of the injured about 50 people are in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Thirty dead people including six women and three children have
been identified.
</P>
<P>
A list of the identified persons has been provided this
afternoon by the Pakistan Railways Headquarters in Lahore, capital
city of Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif today visited the site of
the accident and asked the local government to hold immediate
inquiry into the mishap and submit a report within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
He also directed local hospital authorities and health
departments to ensure provision of the best possible medical
treatment to the injured in the accident.
</P>
<P>
The Governor of North West Frontier Province Muhammad Arif
Bangash expressed today his deep grief and sorrow over the loss of
lives in the accident.
</P>
<P>
Five cars of the train, which was heading for the southern port
city of Karachi, skidded off the tracks outside the rural station
of Mirshah near Khanewal, northeast of Multan in Punjab.
</P>
<P>
The train developed some problem in its brake system just
before approaching the Mirshah station. Due to the fault the
driver could not stop the train and consequently it derailed, the
local press quoted local officials from railway departments as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are still going on and the death toll may
further rise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
