<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM's Envoy Meets Lebanese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 3 (Xinhua) -- An envoy of Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto held a meeting here this morning with
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri on the arrest of some
allegedly Japanese "Red Army" members in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hiroshi Hirabyashi, who arrived in Beirut Sunday night,
conveyed to the Lebanese prime minister a letter from Hashimoto,
according to sources in Hariri's Beirut residence where the
meeting was held.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the anonymous sources said, the Japanese
premier thanked his Lebanese counterpart for the latter's
"personal interference" in the "Red Army" case.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto stressed that if it is proved that the Japanese
arrested by the Lebanese authorities more than half a month ago
are members of the "Red Army," "they should be treated as
criminals in accordance with international laws."
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 30-minute meeting, the Japanese envoy
announced that he discussed with Hariri how to promote the
bilateral relations, especially on the economic and political
levels.
</P>
<P>
On the case of the Japanese "Red Army," the Japanese official
said that he reached an agreement with the Lebanese prime minister
that this case should be handled "on the basis of the laws in
Lebanon and Japan and on the basis of the international laws."
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the identities of these people should
be distinguished and the Lebanese and Japanese governments are
working together in this framework in order to reach results "as
soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
Being reminded that there is no treaty of extraditing
criminals between the two states, the Japanese envoy said that
after finding out those people's identities, "we will see how to
cope with this problem in a way satisfying the two sides."
</P>
<P>
Hirabyashi is expected to have meetings later today with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz and President Elias
Hrawi.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Hirabyashi was carrying evidences that
some of the Japanese arrested by the Lebanese authorities are
members of the "Red Army."
</P>
<P>
A senior Lebanese judicial official expected that the
Japanese envoy will present results of fingerprint analysis
conducted by Japanese investigators.
</P>
<P>
Michel Al-Murr, Lebanon's Vice Prime Minister and Interior
Minister, and Adnan Addoum, the country's state prosecutor,
denied last week that the security forces had taken any members
of the "Red Army" into custody.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the Lebanese authorities detained up
to seven members of the "Red Army" in a search-and-arrest
campaign in the capital on February 15.
</P>
<P>
The radical Japanese group is accused of responsibility for a
series of bloody terror attacks in the Middle East and elsewhere
in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Hashimoto said Saturday he was
puzzled over the handling of the "Red Army" case and was seeking
answers after contradictory statements by senior Lebanese
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
