<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Tablets Found at Guild Hall in North China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Nine stone tablets have been found
in north China's port city of Tianjin at the site of a guild hall
built by businessmen from north China's Shanxi Province in the
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The stone tablets bear inscriptions about the initiation and
development of the guild hall and donations from imperial court
officials and wealthy businessmen from their hometown in Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists, who have also found carvings, painted
pillars, cross beams, and wall paintings at the site, say that the
find will contribute to the study of the economy of the Qing
Dynasty when businessmen from Shanxi played an active role across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The hall, which was named 'Jindu' ('Shanxi Capital'), was built
235 years ago and was the first guild hall built by Shanxi people
in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Guild halls, which started in the Tang Dynasty (618-907), were
agencies set up by people from the same place in other parts of
China who used the halls for gatherings, worship, putting on
plays, conducting business, and for lodgings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Sindh Chief Minister Orders Inquiry Into Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Chief Minister Liaquat Ali Jatoi
of Pakistan's southern Sindh Province today ordered an inquiry
into the bomb blast which damaged the office of a newspaper in
Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Jatoi, who visited the office of the Urdu language newspaper
Qaumi Akhbar earlier today, expressed deep sorrow over the
incident in an official statement.
</P>
<P>
He announced that an inquiry will be carried out into the
incident and a committee will also be formed in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The government will take necessary measures for the enforcement
of law and order in Karachi, the Sindh capital and Pakistan's
largest city.
</P>
<P>
Two employees of Qaumi Akhbar were slightly injured when a
time-bomb went off at 5:53 a.m. in the newspaper's building in
Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Jatoi, during his visit to the scene of the blast, met with the
newspaper's owners, publishers and workers and said security
measures will be adopted for all newspaper offices so that
journalists could work without fear.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the Karachi authorities to apprehend the culprits
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The damage caused by the blast was estimated by the executive
editor of the newspaper, Mukhtar Aqil, at 10 million rupees
(250,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The newspaper's offices, nearby rooms, newly-acquired
computers, scanner, air conditioners and other equipment were
damaged in the blast, Aqil was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
No group or people have claimed responsibility so far for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Sources said bomb disposal experts discovered that the bomb was
a home-made device of a 400-gram TNT flake with a timer.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was placed on the first floor and its impact made a
hole with a diameter of 14 inches, the sources quoted the bomb
experts saying.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, no staff were there when the bomb ripped through
the office, causing major damage to the equipment in the room, the
sources said. The staff usually come to office at around six a.m.
</P>
<P>
Local police in Karachi are investigating the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
