<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Waste Train Starts on Trek Across Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The special train carrying six
containers of nuclear waste left the southern German state of
Baden-Wuertermberg early today for an underground storage depot at
Gorleben in the North.
</P>
<P>
The train will arrive at Dannenberg, Lower Saxony, 20
kilometers west of Gorleben, where the 750 tonnes of spent
nuclear fuel rods from southern Germany and France will be loaded
on heavy lorries before reaching its final destination on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There was no protest as the train departed Waldheim. About 130
people refusing to leave the area were taken into custody before
dawn, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, about 10,000 protesters clogged the streets of
Lueneburg, which is close to Dannenberg. Police reports said that
late Sunday about 500 people blocked access to Dannenberg with
tractors, while others dug up the road linking Gorleben.
</P>
<P>
Authorities mobilized 30,000 police officers to protect the
nuclear transport -- Germany's biggest police operation since
World War II, with the security cost being estimated around 100
million marks (60 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
