<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Shandong Prosper through Patent Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The word "patent" was unknown to
most Chinese farmers in the days before the rural reforms,
initiated by the late senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Now, with the introduction of a market economy, farmers not
only know what patents are, they are making money from them.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Sijiazhuang Village outside the city of Penglai, in
east China's Shandong Province, have earned 280 million yuan (33.7
million US dollars) by selling patented products, and turned over
30 million yuan (3.6 million US dollars) in tax revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
In the rural areas around Yantai, more than 2,000
newly-patented technological methods were used for agricultural
production during the 1992-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
As poorly-educated farmers had difficulty creating inventions
on their own, Shandong farmers bought patents from other parts of
the country, invited talented personnel to the province and
trained their own inventors.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more than 100 young farmers in Sijiazhuang
have been sent to the prestigious Chinese universities such as
Beijing University and Qinghua University. The farmers have
invented 11 patents, among which is the instrument used for
lowering craniocerebral temperature in emergency cases. The device
won a prize for scientific and technological progress from the
provincial authorities.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, village farmers started to transfer their patents, which
not only benefited their own factories, but also brought in hefty
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Launches International Co-operation in Ecological Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Grassland Ecological Research
Institute in northwest China's Gansu Province has been ranked as
No.1 in grass research in the whole country, thanks to academic
co-operations and exchanges with other countries in the field.
</P>
<P>
The institute has sent 56 research fellows, more than half of
its total faculty number, abroad to catch the latest developments
of the field. Eleven of them returned with either a new masters or
doctors degree.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jiang Wenlan applied his experiences with advanced foreign
techniques of animal husbandry to his scientific research. The
research project sponsored by him in the field of grassland animal
husbandry in the Yungui Plateau has achieved world prominence.
</P>
<P>
The institute has established cooperation and exchange
relations with dozens of foreign universities and institutes in
Australia, New Zealand, the United States, and Britain. More than
380 overseas scholars have visited the institute, and over 60 have
worked there for a period of time.
</P>
<P>
The institute has launched 18 co-operative projects with
foreign counterparts, and the grassland agricultural demonstration
zone, set up by a Sino-Australia project with the name of "the
Gansu Grassland Experimental Agricultural Research Station", has
increased its output by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Lantai Lawn Corporation under the institute has grown into
the biggest lawn corporation in China through introducing advanced
techniques from foreign countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
