<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 600 in Quake in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from an
earthquake measuring six degrees on the Richter scale in
northwest Iran Friday afternoon rose to 600 until this morning,
local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA also reported that another
earthquake with a magnitude of 5.2 degrees on the Richter
scale rocked Ardebil province at 22:10 hours local time (18:40
GMT) Sunday, further damaging the areas hit by the earlier
quake.
</P>
<P>
Seifollah Vahid Dastjerdi, head of Iran's Red Crescent Society,
said today that the number of the injured exceeded 2,500.
</P>
<P>
He said that rescue operation is continuing and more than
8,700 tents, 21,800 blankets, 15,300 heaters and lanterns, 50
kilograms of dates, 2,000 cans and 80 tons of bread have been
distributed among the quake victims.
</P>
<P>
The official said that at present 60 ambulances, 127 trucks
and vans and two helicopters are transferring the injured,
relief workers and supplies to and from the quake stricken
region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Switzerland, Britain, Japan as well as some
international relief organizations have voiced readiness to help
the victims.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has decided to earmark 3 billion
rials about (650,000 U.S. dollars) for the quake-hit people of
Ardebil province as part of relief operation.
</P>
<P>
The quake struck cities of Ardebil and Meshkin Shahr and their
surrounding villages, about 600 kilometers northwest of Tehra, at
16:31 hours local time (13:01 GMT) Friday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second major earthquake within a month. On
February 4, a quake measuring 6.1 degrees on the Richter
scale jolted northern Khorasan province, killing a total of 86
people and injuring hundreds others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
