<HEADLINE> Buddhist Leader Warns against Dalai's Visit to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Puchu, president of the
Buddhist Association of China, has severely criticised the Dalai
Lama's upcoming visit to Taiwan from March 22 to 27.
</P>
<P>
"We seriously warn that the Dalai Lama should not continue his
foolish activities that will hurt the feelings of both religious
people and laymen on both sides of the (Taiwan) Straits, and that
will disrupt national unity," Zhao said in a recent speech.
</P>
<P>
He said it is known to all that the Dalai Lama, who lives in
exile, has lost the trust of Buddhist believers by advocating the
independence of Tibet and engaging in activities that will damage
the unity of the motherland, he said.
</P>
<P>
Separatist forces in Taiwan have colluded with the Dalai clique
carrying out various farcical activities, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how much the Dalai Lama will gloss over his visit to
Taiwan, he cannot conceal his real attempt to split the motherland
and disrupt national unity, and he will suffer from his own
actions in the end," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The reunification of the motherland and national unity are the
historical trend of the times and the common aspiration of the
vast legion of patriotic Buddhist believers and laymen on both
sides of the Straits, he said.
</P>
<P>
He admonished some people with the Buddhist Association of
Taiwan, saying they should take a more sensible attitude toward
the invitation of the Dalai Lama to visit Taiwan, in order to
ensure the sound development of Buddhist relations across the
Straits Straits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
