<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Town of Pingyao Well Conserved, ICOMOS Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The ancient town of Pingyao in
north China's Shanxi Province illustrates what can be accomplished
when historical preservation is put into practical use, according
to an expert from the International Council on Monuments and Sites
(ICOMOS).
</P>
<P>
Prof. Tan Tanaka, entrusted by the United States Education,
Science, and Culture Organization (UNESCO), recently made a final
inspection of Pingyao before turning in his nominations for the
World Heritage List, which Pingyao has applied to join.
</P>
<P>
With 3,900 residences built during the Ming (1368-1644) and
Qing (1644-1911) dynasties, the town now reflects a bygone era as
many locals have opened their homes to tourists.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles are banned in the "Street of Ming and Qing Dynasties,"
where a group of typical ancient buildings are located.
</P>
<P>
Hundred-year-old stores are still in use; some of the most
historically significant have been turned into tourist spots. The
Richengchang Exchange Shop, for instance, China's first firm for
exchange and transfer of money, is now a museum of Chinese
exchange shops.
</P>
<P>
Tanaka, an expert on ancient Chinese architecture, said after
the inspection that he was impressed by the "wise conservation" of
the town which is used efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Besides Pingyao, two other sites in China are applying to the
World Heritage List this year: the famous Chinese gardens in
Suzhou, Jiangsu Province, and the ancient town of Lijiang in
Yunnan Province, an 800-year-old city of rivers built by the Naxi
people, who have a unique cultural tradition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Warns of Israeli Schemes on East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Palestinian Council
(PC) Ahmed Korei warned today that Israel is trying to tighten its
grip on East Jerusalem by isolating it from the rest of the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Voice of Arab radio, Korei said that the Israeli
decision on building 6,500 Jewish housing units in Abu Ghoneim in
East Jerusalem is an attempt to create a belt of settlements
around the third holiest city to Islam.
</P>
<P>
"It is aimed at isolating Jerusalem from the rest of the West
Bank and separating the north of the West Bank from its south,"
said the Palestinian official.
</P>
<P>
He said what is even worse than the issue of Abu Ghoneim is the
fact that the Israeli civilian administration two days ago
announced that it would confiscate more lands from the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"There is no point in any negotiations if Israel does not
suspend the building of settlements and the Judaization of the
holy city," Korei said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo agreements, Israel and the Palestinians are to
settle the status of Jerusalem and other sensitive issues in the
peace negotiations set for this month.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
war and wants it to be its "undivided" eternal capital while the
Palestinians insist to have East Jerusalem as the capital of a
future state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official urged the U.S. to shoulder its full
responsibility as a fair sponsor of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be stressed in today's meeting between
U. S. President Bill Clinton and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Washington had expressed its "disappointment" last week over
the Israeli government's decision to go ahead with the
construction of the Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
