<HEADLINE> Damage of Blast Estimated at 250,000 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The extent of damage caused by a
time-bomb blast, which happened early today in a newspaper
building in Pakistan's southern city of Karachi, was estimated at
10 million rupees (250,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Two employees of the Urdu language newspaper Qaynu Akhbar were
slightly injured when the bomb went off at 5:53 a.m. in the
newspaper's building in Karachi, the Sindh capital and Pakistan's
largest city, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The executive editor of the newspaper, Mukhtar Aqil, estimated
that the damages were about 10 million rupees, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper's offices, nearby rooms, newly-acquired
computers, air conditioners and other equipment were damaged in
the blast, Aqil was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
No group or people has claimed responsibility so far for the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Minister of Sindh, Liaquat Ali Jatoi, has visited the
scene of the blast and ordered the local administration to
apprehend the culprits as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the bomb disposal experts discovered that
the bomb was a home-made device of 400 gram TNT with a timer.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was placed on the first floor and its impact made a 14
inch diameter hole, the sources quoted the bomb experts saying.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, there were no staff in the office when the bomb
ripped through the office, causing major damage to the equipment
in the room, the sources said. The staffs usually come to office
at around six a.m.
</P>
<P>
Local police in Karachi are investigating the incident.
</P>
