<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescriptions Found in Dunhuang Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A prescription to treat female
sterility has been found among Buddhist sutras in the Dunhuang
Grottos in northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The treatment, a combination of schisandra fruit and polygala
root, has been proved effective by Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Such prescriptions were common in Buddhist and Taoist classics
found in Dunhuang's Thousand-Buddha Cave in 1899-1900.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars say that Taoism, or the search for longevity,
developed many ways for preserving health, while Buddhism, which
emphasizes spiritual freedom, can be used in conjunction with
psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
Among the newly-found cures are treatments for poisoning caused
by the ingestion of a certain elixir, and for detoxifying internal
organs with the help of medicine and Qigong (deep-breathing
exercises).
</P>
<P>
The elixir poisoning became a serious problem during the
Southern and Northern dynasties (265-589), when the entire upper
class was drinking the elixir to excess to ensure
longevity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
