<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Tops Priority in PNA Future Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority's (PNA) has listed tourism as the most important
industry in the future economic development, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
PNA Deputy International Cooperation Minister Anis Al-Qaq said
in an interview published on today's The Jerusalem Post that the
PNA was establishing vocational training centers in which the
main subjects will be tourism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNA Higher Education Ministry is currently
working on a package of incentives to persuade some university
students to pursue more vocational-based subjects.
</P>
<P>
The main focus in the region will be put on joint tourism
projects in the Aqaba-Eilat-Taba triangular area, the Jordan
Valley, the Dead Sea and Mediterranean areas, where the
Palestinians have the smallest interests of the partners. Al-Qaq
said this meant there had to be a 100 percent cooperation with
Israel, Jordan and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The PNA official regards the tourism potential in the region as
immense, noting that there are about 1 billion Muslims, some 200
million of whom could be attracted to these areas which are rich
in historic and religious sites.
</P>
<P>
However, the development of tourism depended on the peace
process and the final status of Hebron, Bethlehem and, most
significantly, Jerusalem, Al-Qaq pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
