<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Container Throughput to Increase in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's shipping throughput
will be higher in 1997 over 1996, an official of the Hong Kong
Port Development Board (PDB) said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, the official said that
Hong Kong's shipping throughput has remained on the top in the
world shipping business for five consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's total container throughput rose 6.9 percent to
13.41 million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units) in 1996 compared
with 1995.
</P>
<P>
She said that in the first half of 1996, the throughput at Hong
Kong port rose only two percent.
</P>
<P>
The slow growth was due to the higher growth rate of 13 percent
in the same period of 1995 and the tariff readjustment policy made
by the Customs of the Chinese mainland, she said.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of 1996, Hong Kong's shipping throughput was
improved and the growth rate hit eight percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
On the prospects for this year's throughput, she said, an eight
percent growth is expected this year over 1996.
</P>
<P>
She said that one of the factors for the growth is most Hong
Kong companies have been accustomed to the tariff policy
readjustment.
</P>
<P>
She said that the growth will be also promoted by the
improvement of the Sino-U.S. trade relations and the increase of
cargoes shipped on the Beijing-Kowloon Railway to Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orphans' Family in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- "Would you like to be my mum?" a
seven-year-old girl orphan asked her nurse in an orphanage in
the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Qiongqiong, the youngest among the 90 abandoned children in
that orphanage, now says everything to the child-care worker,
Tsongge. It is a far cry from the year when she was taken to the
orphanage from her hometown -- unresponsive, difficult, and nameless.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 orphans live in this make-shift big family, the first
orphanage of its kind located in Nagqu Town in northern Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, various interests in the town set up the orphanage with
donations worth over three million yuan (360,000 US dollars),
including 500,000 yuan (60,000 US dollars) from a Hong Kong company.
</P>
<P>
The orphanage includes a special school with three classrooms,
dormitories, a dining hall, a reading room, an entertainment hall
and a playground. It provides for these children courses on
Tibetan, Chinese, math, civics, and physical education, with
grades from one to three.
</P>
<P>
The children who graduate from the orphanage will go to other
regular primary schools to continue their education, said Daje,
head of the orphanage.
</P>
<P>
The orphans' monthly living expenses are budgeted at 120 yuan
per person, covered by local and state educational and
administrative bodies, which provide for their zanba, a
traditional staple food of Tibet made from barley flour, their
buttered tea, stewed beef, noodles and rice.
</P>
<P>
In addition to their school uniforms, the school authority has
issued to all the orphans leather jackets and Tibetan robes for
special ceremonies and formal occasions.
</P>
<P>
"It's not simply a piece of cake to take care of these
children," Daje said. For many of the orphans, lack of parental
care has resulted in unkempt appearances and bad habits.
</P>
<P>
The 28 child-care workers who cook and wash for the orphans
know that parenting is a 24-hour responsibility, often getting
up in the middle of the night to look after bed-wetting children.
</P>
<P>
"All workers here like staying with these children," Daje said,
"although sometimes we don't always have enough time with our own
families." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Workers Urge HK Govt to Check Student Suicides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Social workers and secondary
school teachers in Hong Kong urged the government to strengthen
counseling programs among students to check the increasing student
suicides.
</P>
<P>
According to an educational profession symposium held in Hong
Kong last weekend, 17 students took their own lives during the
1995-96 school year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a steady rise on the 12 cases in the year
of 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
Wu Pui-wa, a school social worker supervisor, said that
students were facing more emotional problems now while suicides a
decade ago were mainly related to academic results.
</P>
<P>
School social workers dealing with student problems are short.
An official of the Education Department said that there are only
272 social workers for more than 452,800 students in Hong Kong's
400 secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
The number of new cases among the students which were handled
by social workers soared from 5,677 in 1992-93 school year to
8,323 in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
Social workers called for the government's swift actions to
handle student suicides and cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
