<HEADLINE> First Productive Joint Venture Operational in Free-trade Islet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese chemical joint
venture has become operational in Daxie Island, an islet near
Ningbo, a coastal open city in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, co-funded by Daxie Development Corp., a
branch of China International Trust and Investment Co. (CITIC),
and a Japanese chemical corporation with 9.4 million US dollars,
is the first productive enterprise operational in the islet. The
main products of the venture -- adhesives -- can be widely used in
the automobile, home appliance and packaging sectors.
</P>
<P>
Daxie Island is the first national development zone with a
similar status of a free-trade zone. CITIC is the sole developer
of the islet.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some 1,000 ventures have settled in the islet. Key
infrastructure facilities are currently under construction,
including a cross-sea bridge that will soon open. 
</P>
