<HEADLINE> Xinjiang to Promote Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Kashi prefecture and Aksu county,
two major cotton producers in northwest China's Uygur Autonomous
Region of Xinjiang, have planned to produce 475,000 tons of cotton
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Xinjiang battled natural disasters caused by freezing
temperatures, floods, earthquakes and insects plagues, and
harvested 950,000 tons of cotton, accounting for one third of
China's total cotton output.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders of Xinjiang have planned to increase the
cotton planting area from to 866,700 hectares, 66,700 hectares
more than 1996, and develop the cotton production to 1.15 million
tons of total cotton output, 200,000 tons over 1996.
</P>
<P>
An official with the regional government said that to reach the
goal of producing 1.5 million tons of ginned cotton annually, the
government will put in 1.7 billion yuan (about 202 million US
dollars) in exploiting 66,700 hectares of cultivated land every
year. The government will also earmark 30 million yuan (about 3.57
million US dollars) for agriculture technology construction.
</P>
<P>
The central government has offered support in terms of funds
and policy to help the region develop cotton production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
