<HEADLINE> US Company Signs Investment Pact With Arab Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Overseas Private
Investment Corporation has signed an investment guaranty agreement
with the Inter-Arab Investment Fund to help promote the Middle
East peace process, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The pact was signed Sunday in the Omani capital of Muscat by
Mrs. Ruth R. Harkin, President of the Overseas Private Investment
Corporation (OPIC), and Fuad S. Abu Zayyed, chairman of the fund,
Khaleej Time said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper gave no details of the agreement, but it quoted
Harkin as saying that the agreement is mainly aimed at
encouraging peace in the Middle East through backing the efforts
by the Inter-Arab Investment Fund to promote the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC is a self-sustaining U.S. federal agency that
encourages private investments in emerging economies worldwide.
Harkin was appointed OPIC president by U.S. President Bill Clinton
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"Backing this fund will be a critical part of the region's
economic growth and will serve as a foundation for creating
political stability and prosperity", Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
The 45-million-dollar Inter-Arab Investment Fund, which is
managed by California-based Inter-Arab Management International
Company, was formed recently and it will make long-term direct
equity investments in new, expanding or privatizing businesses
in Oman, Jordan, the West Bank and Gaza, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The fund has set up an office in Jordan, another office in
Muscat is to be opened soon.
</P>
<P>
Harkin has expressed her confidence in the ability of the
fund to bring tremendous investments to the Middle East with
OPIC's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC has committed some 200 million U.S. dollars in risk
insurance to a U.S. bank, which was loaning funds to develop an
Omani liquefied natural gas plant.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Harkin, who is making her first visit to Oman, has been
meeting Omani officials to discuss the future of U.S. investment in
the Sultanate, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
