<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Steel Industry to Stress Quality and Marketability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's iron and steel industry,
which in 1996 turned out a record output of more than 100 million
tons of steel, this year will shift its attention from output to
product quality and market competitiveness, and try to achieve a
output-to-sales ratio of 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Beijing today, Liu Qi, minister of
metallurgical industry, said his ministry has set a steel output
target of 100 million tons in 1997, an amount approximately the
same as last year's. This, he said, is intended to encourage steel
enterprises to pay greater attention to product quality and
marketability, rather than to producing more.
</P>
<P>
"We should not only produce 100 millions tons of steel, but
also sell every tone of it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the future development of the iron and steel
industry, Liu stressed structural readjustment in three major
respects.
</P>
<P>
"First, we must adjust the product mix, turning out more
products that come with high added value or are urgently needed on
the market; second, we should upgrade our technologies, trying to
reach international advanced levels by the end of this century,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Third, he said, the industry must make every effort to raise
productivity through internal restructuring, trying to achieve an
annual steel output of 150 tons per worker by the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
"That means China's steelmaking by then will need 800,000
workers only," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions on the current situation of China's
state-owned large and medium-sized steel enterprises, Weng Yuqing,
vice-minister of metallurgical industry, said that their
performance in recent years has fully displayed their ability to
adapt themselves to evolving socialist market economics.
</P>
<P>
"Our ministry is fully confident that reforms in all our
subordinate enterprises have bright prospects," he said.
</P>
<P>
While new and modern enterprises, such as the Handan Iron and
Steel Company in north China's Hebei Province and the Baosteel
Group in east China's Shanghai, have set successful examples in
reforms, he said, old-timers including the Anshan Iron and Steel
Company in northeast China's Liaoning Province and the Wuhan Iron
and Steel Company in central China's Hubei Province have also made
big strides in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that in 1996, 70 percent of the 107 large and
medium-sized state enterprises in China made money, and net
profits for the 107 enterprises in all reached 5.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi said that only one of China's 24 largest steelmakers,
each producing more than one million tons of steel, lost money
last year. The top 24 producers account for 70 percent of the
country's total steel output.
</P>
<P>
China's steel output in 1996 was 101.1 million tons, the
world's largest, with a sales rate of 99 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
