<HEADLINE> NP May Withdraw From S. Africa's Political Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The National Party (NP) may
soon disappear from South Africa's political scene and be
replaced by a new political movement, a senior NP official said
at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Roelf Meyer, former NP Secretary-General, was quoted by the
local daily Sowetan as saying that the NP members would meet at
various federal councils to decide whether they would disband the
party in favor of the new movement which is expected to be
launched in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Meyer is currently heading a task team to establish a possible
realignment in South Africa's opposition politics.
</P>
<P>
Last month, NP leader De Klerk announced a major shake-up to
restructure the party's top leadership, including the disbandment
of the NP's secretariat, in a bid to set up a new political
movement and boost the party membership in 1999 general elections.
</P>
<P>
The NP, a traditionally white party governing South Africa
since 1948, became opposition last May when it withdrew from the
African National Congress-led government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
However, Meyer believed that the proposed new political
movement, would inevitably have Black leadership, which analysts
said could spell an end of an era for De Klerk.
</P>
<P>
"Without significant growth boosted by black numbers, the NP
will continue to be a declining party by 1999, and there will be
proportionally fewer white, coloured and Indian voters to boost
its membership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meyer also dispelled any notion that the movement would be
controlled by the NP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
