<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becomes Increasingly Magnet for Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's economic vitality and
enormous market potential are strong attractions for overseas
investors with an interest in this largest industrial and
commercial center in China, said a municipal foreign trade
official.
</P>
<P>
Contractual foreign investment in the city has topped 10
billion yuan for three consecutive years. In 1996, such investment
in the city totaled 11 billion US dollars, up five percent over
the year before.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the city had approved 15,692
overseas-funded enterprises, with contractual investment amounting
to 45.3 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The official said overseas investment in the city is taking on
several new characteristics:
</P>
<P>
First, the scale of overseas-invested projects continues to
expand. In 1996, the number of projects with pledged investment
surpassing 10 million US dollars had reached 220.
</P>
<P>
Second, the majority of the projects are in the industrial
sector. Among the 1,266 projects approved in 1996, 60 percent were
related to industry. The industrial projects are led by pillar and
high-tech industries, such as automobiles, computers, bio-medicine
and fine chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Third, investment in the service sector, such as real estate
and financing, has increased. Most of the 50 top financial
institutions in the world have opened offices in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
At present, Shanghai has established trade relationships with
40,000 customers in 199 countries and regions. In 1996, Shanghai's
imports and exports totaled 52.87 billion US dollars, a 9.8
percent rise over 1995. Of the total, exports accounted for 13.2
billion dollars and imports, nine billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
A current notable characteristic of foreign trade is that the
imports volume is growing rapidly; in recent years the city was
attentive to the need to introduce state-of-the-art technology,
equipment and industrial raw materials. From 1992 to 1996, imports
into the city grew at an annual rate of 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
