<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Modern China Embraces Easy Transport (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While enjoying the numerous transportation choices available in
cities, many Chinese setting out on lengthier trips opt for the
nation's new and improved railways and highways.
</P>
<P>
Yao's father, a college professor in Beijing, plans to spend
his summer vacation with his son in Dalian, a booming coastal city
in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
"We have so many transportation choices to get to Dalian,
including airplanes and ships," the father said. "Even if we
choose express trains or buses, we need much less time than before
to reach our destination."
</P>
<P>
Statistics from transportation administrations show that China
has 1.18 million kilometers of roads, including over 17,000
kilometers of high grade highways and 3,258 kilometers of
expressways.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 55.5 million people in China traveled by air, up 8.5
percent over the year before. Some Shanghai residents even took
chartered flights to Hong Kong, Singapore and Australia.
</P>
<P>
While the country's developed public transportation system has
made life easier for people on the go, increased incomes have
whetted the appetite of many Chinese people to buy their own cars.
</P>
<P>
A car dealer shop near the Asian Games Village in northern
Beijing listed a record sale of automobiles in 1996, reaching over
10,000, with 5,900 purchased for private use.
</P>
<P>
About 2.5 million Chinese have their own cars, which account
for a quarter of the market share in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most Chinese still use bicycles as their daily means
of transport. The utilitarian, unadorned bikes of the past have
been replaced by more colorful models, and many Chinese prefer to
ride mountain bikes to work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Modern China Embraces Easy Transport (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Like most Beijingers, 10-year-old
Yao Ziqi has grown accustomed to the easy convenience of
taxis. But he likes to tell the story of the day he was born, when
his father carried his pregnant mother on a bicycle to the
hospital because the capital city had so few cabs.
</P>
<P>
Now, Yao says, flagging down taxis is part of his everyday
life, used for family outings or when he visits his grandparents'
house five bus stops away.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has the country's largest taxi fleet -- over 60,000
vehicles in 1,600-plus taxi companies. And what was once a rich
man's privilege has become an affordable service for many
residents.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey released by the Chinese Cities' Taxi
Association shows that China has a total of 500,000 taxis, spread
throughout 803 cities in 30 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In many cities, more than 60 percent of the residents often
take taxis; in some areas, the figure is as high as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Riding in taxis has even become fashionable on the streets of
Lhasa, the capital of western China's Tibet Autonomous Region,
where residents of the Himalayan city like to go shopping during
the traditional Lunar New Year, which coincides with the Tibetan
New Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Invests More in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan invested 370 million US
dollars last year, eight percent more than the previous year, in
Xiamen City, a port city of eastern China's Fujian Province,
according to the Xiamen city government.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the coastal city's trade with Taiwan rose 27 percent
to 1.6 billion US dollars, according to Kong Changcai, director of
the Taiwan Affairs Office of the Xiamen city government.
</P>
<P>
He said that as more than 270,000 Taiwan compatriots visited
Xiamen last year, a rise of more than ten percent over the
previous year, Xiamen has already become one of the major gates
for Taiwan compatriots to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen is a special economic zone where flexible policies are
being pursued to encourage investors from Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan
and overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, over 1,600 Taiwan business people came to Xiamen to
conduct trade and investment talks," he said. "The number exceeded
that of Hong Kong business people for the first time."
</P>
<P>
The Xiamen government attaches great importance to the
promotion of Xiamen-Taiwan economic cooperation and has adopted a
series of measures to ensure that the legitimate rights and
interests of Taiwan investors in Xiamen were protected, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that of the 127 complaints received by the city's
Complaint Center for Taiwan Compatriots last year, 96 percent of
them had been successfully resolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
