<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislator Calls for Rejuvenation of Ship-Building Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese legislator urges
enacting a law to instill more vitality into the country's
ship-building industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Youjun, a National People's Congress (NPC) deputy from
Shanghai, suggested China's top legislature provide a legal
guarantee for the rejuvenation of the country's ship-building
industry when discussing with other deputies Premier Li Peng's
government work report to the current annual NPC session.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a computer expert working for Shanghai Shipyard, said
China boasts a coastal line with thousands of kilometers, and the
demands for a faster developing shipbuilding industry come from
various sectors like ocean shipping, off-shore development and
defense of coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the shipbuilding industry is a labor-intensive
one with a highly concentrated combination of labor, capital and
technology, and that China has been emerging as a rising
competitor in the world's ship-building market as its shipyards
have done good work and are operating at low labor costs.
</P>
<P>
China's shipyards are confronted with great opportunities since
90 percent of the world trade volume today goes to ocean shipping,
which is expected to flourish in the next century.
</P>
<P>
China's shipbuilding industry has shown robust growth over the
past few yeas, with an output value exceeding 25 percent annually.
On the international market, the total tonnage of orders are
placed to Chinese shipbuilders. So China has, for fifth
consecutive year, ranked the third in term of orders it received,
only next to Japan and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
To date, three shipbuilding bases have been established in
China, namely, Shanghai in east China, Dalian in northeast China,
and Guangzhou in south China, which are also three major ports in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The development of the shipbuidling industry must have the
backing of the some 50 industries, involving metallurgical,
machinery, electronic and telecommunications, and many other
industries, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that ship building, if designated as a pillar
industry, will help promote the development of other industries,
and the government should increase input in the industry and
strengthen its macroeconomic management.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it has been reported that the drafting of a law
concerning rejuvenation of the shipbuilding industry is under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
