<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Set Up National Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's cabinet has
approved a plan to set up an eight-member National Security
Council in charge of preparing strategies to safeguard the
small Gulf country and "serve the requirements of national
security in all fields," according to a cabinet statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement, released Sunday night after Kuwait's cabinet
weekly meeting, said that the council "aims at guaranteeing the
safety and security of the country and to set strategic
policies, programs and plans to achieve that goal."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti State Minister for Cabinet Affairs Abdel Aziz
al-Dakhil said the decision was made in view of the
"developments of the present stage and changes prevailing in
the area and their impact on stability of Kuwait." The
council would be entrusted with preparing statements, information
and researches needed in security-related fields.
</P>
<P>
The council, to be chaired by Crown Prince and Prime Minister
Sheikh Saad Al-Abdulah Al-Salem Al-Sabah, will included deputy
prime ministers, foreign minister, defense minister, finance
minister, interior minister, national guards chief and president
of the national security body.
</P>
<P>
The draft decree was referred to the Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah for final approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
