<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beibu Gulf Develops Pillar Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Beibu Gulf, once an agricultural
area between Vietnam and China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
and Hainan Province, is revealing its economic strength by
developing pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
The gulf area has one of the six largest oil-gas fields in
China and one of the eight largest iron mines in Asia. The city of
Beihai in Guangxi has a proved reserve of 30 million tons of
quartz sand, 271 million tons of gypsum, 189 million tons of
pottery clay and 1.26 million tons of ilmenite.
</P>
<P>
With approval from the central government, Beihai has invested
10 billion yuan building a thermal power plant with a generating
capacity of 1.2 million kw, as well as a chemical fiber plant and
the third phase of the Beihai Port.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Province is building a heavy industry corridor which
includes a synthetic ammonia plant with an annual capacity of
300,000 tons, a urea plant that can produce 520,000 tons a year, a
key cement works, a fertilizer plant and a nylon mill. Some
projects have gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
A new highway linking the cities of Haikou and Yangbu in Hainan
Province will soon open to traffic to meet the needs of the
industrial corridor.
</P>
<P>
As the largest city in the Beibu Gulf, Zhanjiang in Guangdong
Province is working to become an industrial base with auto, sugar,
foodstuffs, building materials, petro-chemistry, power and durable
electronic products as its pillar industries by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Some regional leaders predict that by the early 21st century,
the gulf area will emerge as a new economic center similar to the
heavy industrial belt at the Bohai Bay in north China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
