<HEADLINE> Icy Heilongjiang Becomes Hot Spot for Winter Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A record 100,000 Chinese and
overseas tourists ventured to China's northernmost province of
Heilongjiang in January and February, hoping to ski, hunt, and
take in the ice lantern and snow-carving shows.
</P>
<P>
The figure is double that of the same period of last year,
according to Ning Shimin, director of the Provincial Tourism
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The boom in business meant an 80-100 percent occupancy rate to
the over 30 star-rated hotels in the province, and packed all of
the chartered flights between Hong Kong and Harbin, the provincial
capital city, during the Spring Festival period from Feb. 7-11.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Yabuli Skiing Resort, the site of last
year's Third Asian Winter Games, has attracted over 20,000
tourists since January.
</P>
<P>
The program "Winter Tour Around Jingbo Lake," which included
hunting, fishing and water sports, drew a great number of
travelers, including a 140-member group from Singapore. 
