<HEADLINE> Private Business Expands in Southwest China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Private business has been
expanding at an average rate of over ten percent over the past ten
years in the city of Chongqing, an industrial hub in southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the city had 1.04 million individual
business people, and 13,676 private firms employing 130,000
people, and they generated a total of 6.66 billion yuan in output
value with 21.89 billion yuan of business turnover.
</P>
<P>
Individual businesses usually employ less than three people
each, while private enterprises employ more than eight people in
China.
</P>
<P>
The city's individual businesses and private enterprises, that
formerly engaged in commerce and trade, catering services and
social services, have now expanded to a wider fields including the
production of spare parts of automobiles and motors, development
of real estate and tourism resources and intermediary services.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, 320 individual business
people and private enterprises are engaged in production of
electronics, bio-engineering and green food, which generate 600
million yuan of output value, and provide 500 million yuan worth
of commodities for the country's exports a year.
</P>
<P>
The individual business people and private enterprises supply
the local market with an overwhelming share of vegetables,
poultry, eggs, fruits, meat-related foodstuffs and grain.
</P>
<P>
When the private sector expands in both scope and scale and
demonstrates great development potentials, it has attracted an
increasing number of skilled workers, university professors,
technicians and scientists, local sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
