<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Chinese Provinces Report Bumper Fishery Harvests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province's fishery business
reported another record season last year, with a total output of
4.15 million tons of fish, shrimps and crabs, an increase of nine
percent over the year before.
</P>
<P>
The province's fishery production was valued at 80 billion yuan
last year, up ten percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province's deep-sea fishing production rose by 69
percent in 1996 to 150,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, in east China, has a coastline of over 3,000 km,
one-sixth of the national total. It has some 600 breeding farms,
300 feed factories, 800 frozen storage outlets, and 1,500 aquatic
products processing factories.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zhejiang Province, another coastal province in east
China, reported its 11th consecutive outstanding year for fishery
in 1996. Its aquatic products totaled 3.42 million tons, 7.5
percent over the previous year. Aquatic products netted in through
deep-sea fishing stood at 150,000 tons, 22 percent more than in
1995.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Zhejiang provincial government attributed
the province's achievements in fishery to fishermen's initiative
for buying boats through a share-holding system. The farmers
jointly owned over 6,000 boats, which enabled them to cast nets in
the north Pacific Ocean and waters off the coast of western Africa.
</P>
<P>
The seawater farming on tidal flats and off the coast also
contributed a large share of the province's fishery output, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Zhejiang had a total of 53,300 ha of seawater
farming area, which turned out over 770,000 tons of aquatic
products, 17 percent more than in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
