<HEADLINE> China Opens Evening Services for Foreign Exchange Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese bank here will
extend its service hours for foreign currency trading to 10:30
p.m. beginning from February 28.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Communications' Shanghai branch is offering the
extra time to allow Chinese people to buy and sell foreign
currencies in world markets, via telephone, through a trading
account with the bank.
</P>
<P>
"This move is a signal that China has linked its foreign
exchange market to world markets in Tokyo, Hong Kong, Singapore,
London and New York," said an official with the bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank began operation of the telephone service on January
12, and the service has since become increasingly popular,
increasing the bank's number of foreign currency trading accounts
by 30.6 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The units of foreign exchange trading shot up 20 percent during
the period, with 17 percent conducted via telephone.
</P>
<P>
A minimum of 300 US dollars-worth of foreign exchange is
required for trading at night, which runs from 6 p.m. to 10:30
p.m., according to the bank official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
