<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Warns Arafat Against Declaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has warned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
against declaring independence in reaction to Israel's building
plan in eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Likud Central Committee meeting held in Tel
Aviv Sunday night, Netanyahu said Arafat's declaring of
independent state would be a grave mistake that could halt
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We will know how to react and we have a very good
answer," he said, referring to the warning issued by Arafat
earlier in the day that he could declare independence unilaterally
in reaction to Israel's plan to build a Jewish settlement in Har
Homa area in the disputed eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Israeli President Ezer Weizman also cautioned
Arafat against declaring a Palestinian state now. "It will be
a terrible mistake. This is not the right time. It would
be a shame that something which seems important to the
Palestinians should disrupt the peace process," he said during
a visit of the soldiers wounded in south Lebanon fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu promised about 2,000 enthusiastic party
supporters that Israel would build in Jerusalem and anywhere
else it decided to.
</P>
<P>
He denied that he had reached a deal over the Har Homa
project with Arafat, in which Israel reportedly agreed to
widen the scope of further troop withdrawals on the West
Bank in return for Arafat's agreement to the Har Homa
project.
</P>
<P>
"I have not promised Arafat anything," claimed Netanyahu,
adding bureaucratic procedures had been sped up in order to
start the Har Homa building immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Likud gathering was convened in a show of support to
the prime minister and his policies in the wake of Har
Homa controversy, and the current "Bar-On scandal" that
threatens to topple his government.
</P>
<P>
According to the exposure by the state-run Television Channel
I, the abortive appointment of Jerusalem attorney Roni Bar-On
as the Attorney General in January involved a plea-bargain
deal arranged between the government and the influential Shas
leader Aryeh Deri, who has been facing criminal investigation
on fraud and bribe-taking.
</P>
<P>
Deri reportedly pushed for the appointment of Bar-On, who
had promised a plea bargain to him in future trials, by
conditioning Shas' support of the Hebron agreement on Bar-On's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
Bar-On, also a member of Likud Central Committee, was
indeed appointed the Attorney General by the cabinet, but
he resigned automatically only tow days later due to the
strong protests over his insufficient professional qualification
and political background.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu remained confident that the government would
get through the crisis. "We shall get over these difficult
times, I promise you," he told the supporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
