<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Pakistani Friendship Stands Long: Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A veteran Pakistani diplomat who
left China in January of this year after spending 14 years here
described the country as open, friendly and rapidly-changing and a
place where he met thousands of friends.
</P>
<P>
Habib-ur-Rahman, former Minister of the Pakistani Embassy in
Beijing, said in a letter to Xinhua News Agency that throughout
his entire stay in China, he experienced the sincere friendship
between the people of Pakistan and the Chinese. He also said that
he was deeply impressed by the fast changes that China witnessed
during his tenure here.
</P>
<P>
Habib was sent to study at the Beijing Language Institute in
China by Pakistani foreign ministry in 1977.
</P>
<P>
As a diplomat, Habib was posted in China three times, from 1977
to 1982, 1983 to 1987, and 1993 to this January.
</P>
<P>
"A long time ago, like many Pakistani people, I was looking
forward to knowing China and her people," he recalled in his
letter.
</P>
<P>
During my study at the Beijing Language Institute, Habib
realized that his Chinese friends were eager to learn about
Pakistan, he said. "I made thousands of friends in my 14 years in
China."
</P>
<P>
He said that offers of assistance were extended to him wherever
he went, and that he learned to rely on his Chinese friends for
help, including those from the leading organs of the Communist
Party of China (CPC), the Foreign Ministry, the Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries, the Diplomatic
Personnel Service Bureau, the Islamic Association of China, the
State Education Commission and many other culture, education and
research institutes.
</P>
<P>
"It's very pleasant to work in China, because China is a true
friend and the most sincere neighbor of Pakistan. Not only the
Chinese government has offered a lot of help to Pakistan, but the
Chinese people cherish deep feelings of friendship toward the
country," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
About two years ago, Habib suffered a serious heart problem
which required surgery.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Zhu at Fuwai Hospital in Beijing recommended that Habib be
treated in either the United States or Germany, or go back to
Pakistan. Habib opted to stay in China and asked Zhu to perform
the operation.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to have the operation done by my Chinese friends. I
didn't want to go to any other countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu and ten other medical experts formed a surgical team to
treat Habib. Fifty days after the operation, Habib walked out of
the hospital, and now he can walk, run and attend in a variety of
activities.
</P>
<P>
"China has given me a new life," Habib said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
