<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Becomes Leading Vegetable Supplier of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen now supplies about 70
percent of the fresh vegetables sold in Hong Kong everyday,
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Other figures indicate that 90 percent of the leaf vegetable
consumption in Hong Kong comes from its neighbor to the north.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, taking advantage of its relatively cheaper labor
resources, has set up many well-equipped processing plants for the
more expensively-packaged fresh vegetables, which have been
favorites among Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
The quarantine authorities at the ports of entry are strictly
examining goods, banning the use of over 40 types of pesticides
and over 100 sorts of compound pesticides for vegetables sold to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We'll do our utmost to ensure the quality of the vegetables to
Hong Kong," said Liu Zhaojing, an official with Wenjingdu Port,
where 60 percent of the vegetables pass through.
</P>
<P>
A quota system is in effect to prevent market surplus, and last
year's quota of vegetables sold to Hong Kong from Shenzhen was
80,786 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
