<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Breeds More Rare Monkeys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Twelve of 16 artificially-bred
baby langur monkeys, one of the world's rarest long-tailed
primates, have survived after their birth last year in a special
breeding center in China.
</P>
<P>
The center, the largest of its kind in China, in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, now has 93 of the monkeys, which are
under top state protection. The figure accounts for one fourth of
all those raised in captivity in the world, according to the
"China Environmental News."
</P>
<P>
One of the female monkeys has given birth 12 times, and now has
a family of four generations, also a rarity.
</P>
<P>
The monkey, formally known as presbytis francdisi, is from the
langur family, with jet-black fur and a tail longer than its
body. Slimly built, it lives on a diet of tree leaves. The species
is native to southern China.
</P>
<P>
China set up the center in Wuzhou City in 1991, with a total
planned investment of 30 million yuan (3.61 million US
dollars). To date, more than three million yuan has been spent on
construction.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists began artificial breeding of the monkey in
1976, and a number of monkeys raised by the center have been sent
as "envoys of friendship" to zoos in Japan, the United States,
Canada and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
