<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deputies Advise Caution about Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Approval and appreciation laced
with cautionary advices have replaced serious concern and a strong
desire to address inquires on the issue of inflation at the
ongoing session of the Chinese legislature.
</P>
<P>
This is indicated by what legislators say in group discussions
and in interviews. They are here attending the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
High inflation was a serious concern among deputies at NPC
sessions of a recent past when rates stood at 13, 21.7 and 14.8
percent respectively in 1993, 1994 and 1995. Inflation came down
to 6.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"As Premier Li Peng said in his government work report, last
year, while prices came down speedily, the entire national economy
maintained a sustained, rapid growth, with our GDP reaching more
than 6,770 billion yuan, a growth of 9.7 percent over the previous
year," said Deputy Zeng Haorong, who is also mayor of Haikou,
capital of Hainan province. "This proves that we've achieved an
economic soft landing, that we've made a good beginning in our
effort to change the mode of growth, and that people's living
standard has genuinely improved."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Zhang Zhongli, president of the Shanghai Academy of
Social Sciences and a prestigious economist, said that maintaining
a high growth rate and driving down inflation at the same time is
a "remarkable achievement" on the part of the government.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that governments at all levels are not powerless
about price control. "For local governments, one of the things
they should do is to strengthen supervision over markets and
prices, while endeavoring to increase the supply of farm produce,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Yu Hanqing, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Municipal
People's Congress of Chongqing, said local governments'
supervision over prices should be "appropriate" so that both
consumers and producers are satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Deputies also warned against relaxation on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"Some factors that drive up inflation still exist, and China is
not entirely free from cycles of overheating and stagnation
consequent upon a loosening or tightening of macro controls," said
Deputy Cai Lulun, president of the Hunan branch of the People's
Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
"Effective measures are still needed to restrict money supply
and investment increases," he said. "The government must pursue
unswervingly appropriately tight financial and monetary policies."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
