<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Controls Tourism Spot Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Waste water will no longer be
drained into West Lake, a well-known scenic spot in East China's
Zhejiang Province, according to the local government.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection department of Hangzhou, the
capital of Zhejiang Province, said that the last sewage
source around the 5.2 square kilometer lake has been eliminated
after nearly six months' effort.
</P>
<P>
The city government has laid 9.4 kilometers of drainage pipes
around the lake to divert waste water, while 300,000 cubic meters
of water from the nearby Qiangtang River is being channeled into
West Lake for cleaning daily.
</P>
<P>
A newly completed project, with a two-kilometer-long drainage
pipe, will divert rain water and sewage in the area into the
city's sewer system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of pollutant plants around the lake have
moved out, and motor-driven pleasure-boats have been replaced by
battery-operated ones, to preserve the lake's natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, the lake's transparency now reaches 50 to 60
centimeters, and air quality around the lake has improved, and
flocks of birds that had left the lake area have since returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
