<HEADLINE> Oil City Outlines Urban Development Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Daqing, a city built on the heels
of the successful Daqing Oilfield in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, is developing alternative key industries
involving oil and petrochemcial production.
</P>
<P>
Daqing's Mayor Qian Lihua said the city hopes to draw up an
economic development plan supported by oil, petrochemical and
alternative industries, in a move to build Daqing, the largest
oilfield in China, into a modern high-tech city in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
In the construction drive, Daqing will redouble its efforts to
succeed in ten areas, including realizing a higher economic growth
rate than the national average, and trying to be rated among the
highest in economic place rating among major cities and in per
capita gross domestic product (GDP) -- the value of goods and
services produced).
</P>
<P>
Scientific and technological progress will contribute more than
70 percent to the city's economic growth, while high-tech
industries will become a leading force in the city's economic
structure and GDP, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
The city also expects to make marked progress in economic
cooperation and foreign trade development, fast economic expansion
in the suburbs, notable improvement in cultural and ethical
progress and in urban construction, success in the establishment
of a market economic structure, and creating a rich and diverse
life for its residents and a fine environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
