<HEADLINE> East China City To Improve State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A greater effort to improve
businesses in Zibo, an important industrial city in east China's
Shandong Province, has helped developments in the city's
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In order to upgrade its industrial structure, the city placed
more importance on transforming the traditional industries, and in
1996 its state-owned enterprises earned record profits, which
increased 36 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It also launched large-scale technological improvements in its
six leading industries, with investment in them in 1996 reaching
3.6 billion yuan, a 20 percent increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The city has completed 166 technological development projects,
83 of which are at an advanced level.
</P>
<P>
The city has come up with a series of policies to encourage
enterprises to develop new products and has established
enterprises groups to promote improvements in local enterprises'
structures.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of shares is expected to help local enterprises
increase the ability to raise money, and 82 enterprises in the
city have so far joined the system, with five of them having been
listed in other cities' exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
