<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Croatia to Help Reconstruct Bosnia- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Croatia today
stressed the importance of cooperation in the reconstruction of
Bosnia- Herzegovina and pledged to encourage their companies
concerned to immediately develop some projects.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina was a major topic of the
talks between Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and his
Croatian counterpart Zlatko Matesa here today.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders stressed that it was important that war criminals
in that country be brought to trial in the Hague, because as long
as the criminals remain at large, then there is always a threat to
peace, Malaysian foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told a
news conference after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Regretting that agreements reached earlier that Malaysia and
Croatia should join together to undertake various construction
projects in Bosnia-Herzegovina could not proceed as expected, both
leaders emphasized the importance of getting these joint ventures
to move ahead, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders pledged to encourage the companies concerned to
immediately develop some projects.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the Croatian side suggested that Malaysia, with
some experiences in developing small businesses, should help
Bosnia- Herzegovina and Malaysia agreed to send soon a delegation
to Bosnia- Herzegovina to identify what possible types of small
businesses can be introduced in that country so that disarmed
soldiers, large in number without jobs, could participate in.
</P>
<P>
Bilaterally, the two leaders agreed that there has been some
progress in the areas of bilateral cooperation since the last
visit of Mahathir to Croatia last April but more needs to be done,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders decided to intensify the cooperation in three
specific areas where they believe that Croatia and Malaysia have
some advantages and the areas are power generation, ship-building
and construction.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said it was hoped that companies of the two countries
can develop joint ventures to work on these projects not only in
Croatia and Malaysia but also in third countries.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian government has also accepted the suggestion made
by the Malaysian side that they should also accept another
designated Malaysian airline to fly to Croatia instead of the
Malaysian Airline and the AirAsia, the second Malaysian airline,
is the possible designated airline for that.
</P>
<P>
Zlatko Matesa, leading a 12-member delegation comprising three
ministers, two vice ministers, senior government officials and
businessmen, arrived here last night for a three-day visit to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During Mahathir's visit to Croatia, a total of five Memoranda
of Understanding (MOUs), three instruments of agreement and a
joint venture agreement were signed.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's national car "Proton" also penetrated the Croatian
market with the first export of 200 cars to Niva Holdings, the
Proton distributor in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Kuala Lumpur and Zagreb also signed an agreement
for partial abolition of visa requirements, allowing people of
both countries to travel for 30 days without the need for visa.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade has been improving. The trade volume
increased from 5.12 million US dollars in 1994 to 6.31 million US
dollars in 1995 and further to 10 million US dollars last year,
with trade balance in favor of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Croatia also signed an air services agreement last
year, providing both national carriers seven flights a week
between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0212 </DOCNO>
