<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Nations to Form Indian Ocean Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A new international organization
will be formally launched by 14 countries belonging to three
continents of Asia, Africa and Oceania when their foreign
ministers meet in Mauritius between March 5 and 7, The Times of
India reported today.
</P>
<P>
With the avowed goal of facilitating regional cooperation, this
new organization will be called Indian Ocean Rim Association for
Regional Cooperation (IORARC).
</P>
<P>
India, along with Mauritius, South Africa, Australia,
Singapore, Oman and Kenya, have been working towards the
establishment of IORARC during the last two years. In the
meantime, seven other countries -- Sri Lanka, Malaysia, Indonesia,
Yemen, Tanzania, Mozambique and Madagascar -- joined the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
Going by its proposed charter, the IORARC will have four main
features:
</P>
<P>
-- The highest decision-making body of the organization will be
the ministerial council of foreign ministers who will meet at
least once every two years.
</P>
<P>
-- It will have a unique three-pronged approach in working in
the sense that it involves a coordinated endeavor of officials,
academicians and businessmen of the member countries. The point is
that officials alone will not be responsible for its functioning.
</P>
<P>
-- Though the IORARC aims to be "universal," involving all the
Indian Ocean countries, the membership will be restricted to begin
with. The underlying assumption is that there should be a "core
group approach" for the sake of viability and efficiency. The
objective is to realize goals in a phased manner.
</P>
<P>
-- All cooperative endeavors will be voluntary in nature. In
fact, 10 such ventures have already been identified, with India
responsible for four of them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
