<HEADLINE> Peruvian President Flies to Dominican Republic on Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
flew to the Dominican Republic Sunday to discuss possible asylum
for guerrillas holding 72 hostages in Lima.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori held talks with his Dominican counterpart Leonel
Fernandez to discuss a possible Dominican refuge for the
guerrillas if there is a deal to peacefully end the crisis, a
Dominican government source said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the meeting, Fernandez's office
said only that the presidents had touched on the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori gave a brief explanation of the current situation of
the talks between the Peruvian government negotiator and the
representatives of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement
guerrillas, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
He said in Peru Sunday that the Dominican Republic would not be
a likely destination for the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
About 15 guerrillas seized the Japanese Embassy in Lima on
December 17. They freed several hundred captives but still hold 72
men. 
