<HEADLINE> Clinton to Declare Parts of Arkansas Disaster Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
declaring parts of Arkansas a disaster area after tornados tore
through the state Saturday, killing 24 people and injuring
hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
A White House spokesman said the president also planned to
visit his home state Tuesday to view the damage.
</P>
<P>
The state's capital Little Rock, Arkadelphia and smaller towns
around were the most hit area.
</P>
<P>
The death toll was still climbing as rescue workers worked in
rain today to pull away the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people were injured and hundreds of homes,
business and other structures were destroyed or damaged along a
437-kilometer path from Hempstead County in the southwest to
Greene County in the state's northeastern corner.
</P>
<P>
At least 10,000 electricity customers were left with no power
after the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee has called up the Arkansas
National Guard to aid with security and cleanup. Six counties have
been declared disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
The storms also struck Mississippi, Kentucky, Tennessee, Ohio
and part of Texas, killing as many as 16 people and causing heavy
property damage.
</P>
<P>
Residents in parts of Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia and
Tennessee were evacuated because of torrential rains and flash
floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
