<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Growth In Northwest China's Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The mobile telephone and pager
are no longer symbols of large fortunes or social status in
landlocked Gansu Province, which added 23,000 cellular phone
customers and 81,000 for pagers last year.
</P>
<P>
It also added 148,000 phone customers and expanded its
program-controlled switching service to include all counties.
</P>
<P>
To ensure growth in the telecommunications industry, Gansu
spent 1.31 billion yuan (about 154 million US dollars) in the
telecom sector last year, with the telephone switching capacity
being increased by 174,000 lines and five local phone networks
being expanded, while 4,018 km of optical cables and three digital
microwave trunks were added to the province.
</P>
<P>
The packet exchange network now covers all cities and counties,
and the digital and date network (DDN) service is available in all
cities and in 55 counties.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 1997, a visual-conference TV system was
imported from the United States for 13 prefectures and counties in
Gansu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
