<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Improve Transport Link in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is fully prepared to
improve linkages in all modes of transport with all countries in
and outside the Southeast Asia region, Myanmar Minister for
Transport Thein Win was quoted by official paper The New Light of
Myanmar as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the second ASEAN Transport Ministers Meeting in
Chiang Mai, Thailand, last Friday, Thein Win reaffirmed Myanmar's
full and irreversible commitment to becoming a full member of
ASEAN, determining to fully cooperate with all ASEAN member
countries in the promotion of transport operations.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, The Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal initiated by Thailand, Myanmar is among
countries where national highways throughout the ASEAN and
Southeast Asian mainland are to be linked, which also include
Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is seen as an attempt to facilitate the transport
of goods over land through these countries to ensure that the
near-zero tariff set under the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) will
lead to freer trade by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tachilek-Kengtung Road in Shan state of Myanmar
bordering Thailand is being upgraded with a Thai loan. The road
will lead through Chiang Rai up to Bangkok and may also be used as
a connection infrastructure to China via the Kengtung-Mongla Road.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
