<HEADLINE> Shandong Farmers Become "Experts for Hire" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Yinji Township, Gaotang
County, in east China's Shandong Province often attend lectures on
greenhouse vegetable growing given by Wang Dianwen, deputy head of
the town in charge of vegetable production.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Wang is one of the 4,000 farmers from Shouguang
County, also in Shandong, who were invited to be township
officials or vegetable experts in China's inland provinces and
autonomous regions last year.
</P>
<P>
Of these farmers, 80 became contracted deputy township
heads in charge of science and technology work and three became
deputy magistrates in other areas.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 70 percent of vegetable growers in Shouguang,
a rich county famous for its greenhouse vegetables, have become
experts after years of study and practice.
</P>
<P>
With the development of vegetable growing in other provinces,
many provincial or county officials have invited experts from
Shouguang in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
In turn, Shouguang County received 60 million yuan (about 7.5
million US dollars) in 1996 from sending such experts to other
areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Zhongxin, a farmer in Sunjiaji Township, was invited to be
deputy magistrate of Wuyi County in Hebei Province in 1993.
</P>
<P>
When Wu returned home he recalled his experience in the Hebei
county proudly. He said his family has been farmers for
generations, and his grandfathers would never have dreamt of being
county officials.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
