<HEADLINE> Thai PM Vows to Push Ahead Office Automation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh Sunday vowed to fully computerize Thai state agencies
in three years to keep Thailand abreast of other members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit affirmed the need to update the government information
technology, which is part of the government's "IT2000" scheme, to
improve the working efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The computerized network would help cabinet ministers to save
time from paperwork so that they can concentrate more on
decision-making on policy matters, Chavalit was quoted as saying
by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that Singapore has developed its
computer network, while Malaysia and the Philippines also have
moved in that direction.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit indicated that the Thai system should be in place by
the year 2000, but did not elaborate on the size of investment.
</P>
