<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Arrives in Washington amid Middle East Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat arrived in Washington Sunday amid an explosive tension
triggered by Israel's approved housing project in Arab east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who flew here after attending an emergency session of
the Cairo-based Arab League, will meet U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday morning to express his concern over the Israeli decision
to construct 6,500 homes for Jewish settlers in Har Homa in east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader has denounced the Israeli plan, saying
the settlement issue is an attempt by Israel to blast the peace
process to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
"We say that there can be no peace without Jerusalem and no
peace with settlements. Settlements and peace do not go
together, and there will be no peace as long as Israel violates
our rights in Jerusalem," Arafat told the Arab League session in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish an independent state in
the occupied territories with east Jerusalem as its capital, but
Israel has declared the whole Holy city as its capital since
taking hold of the east part of it even though the international
community refused to recognize its claim.
</P>
<P>
Arafat suggested that he could declare a Palestinian state in
response to Israel's housing project in Arab east Jerusalem,
</P>
<P>
"We are supposed to declare the setting up of a Palestinian
state in five years, but what would happen if I declare it right
here? What would he (Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu)
do then? It's tit-for-tat, and we have our weapons, too." he said.
</P>
<P>
The 22-member Arab League issued a statement after the
session asking "countries that give economic and financial aid
to Israel to stop this aid because it will be used in settlement
plans on occupied Arab lands."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hanan Ashrawi, the Palestinian minister of higher
education, urged the Clinton administration to take a clear
position on Jerusalem and settlement issues, denouncing Israel's
recent move on settlement.
</P>
<P>
"We take it for granted the U.S. policy and peace agreements
clearly indicate that building of a new settlement in Jerusalem
is not only illegal but is extremely destructive and an act of
extreme provocation and incitement that could lead the whole
peace process to unravel," she said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has criticized Israel's approval of housing
construction in Arab east Jerusalem, saying it complicated an
already complex situation and was not a step to "build
confidence and trust." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
