<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Urged to Push Basic Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government should improve
basic education for the masses by 2001 to realize its 12-year
compulsory education policy, according to Thailand's National
Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission recently publicized the Eighth National
Education Development Plan, requesting the Thai government to
provide basic education and occupational training for more people
in 1997-2001.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, at least 90 percent of 3- to 5-year-old
children will gain access to pre-primary education and at least 95
percent of youngsters aged 12-14 will have opportunities to study
at secondary schools in 2001.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Thai government must offer secondary education
for at least 50 percent of workers who complete primary education,
especially those aged 20-45, and provide occupational training for
others in 2001.
</P>
<P>
In 2001, at least 20 percent of people aged 18-24 will have
access to higher education and 40 percent of new undergraduate
students will enter science and technology faculties.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Education Ministry is also expected to adjust the
curriculum in line with the communities' needs, focus on
self-learning improvement monitoring and evaluating systems, and
offer scholarships and training for more teachers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
