<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling MPs Ordered to Back Govt in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main ruling party has
ordered all of its lawmakers to support the coalition government
led by Sher Bahadur Deuba during the upcoming vote of confidence
in parliament.
</P>
<P>
President of the Nepali Congress (NC) party Girija Prasad
Koirala Sunday issued a whip directing all MPs of his party to
attend the winter session of parliament, which is to start later
today, and vote in favor of the government.
</P>
<P>
The party whip by the NC chief came out after over a dozen of
NC MPs threatened to be absent from the parliament session if
Deuba, who is also an NC leader, does not reduce the size of his
47-member cabinet before the session in accordance with the
party's decision.
</P>
<P>
Deuba last week vowed to reshuffle his cabinet only after his
three-party government obtains a proposed vote of confidence in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to seek the vote of confidence for his
government during the winter session as it had been reduced into
the minority status by an opposition-sponsored no-confidence
motion last December.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deuba Sunday registered a motion at the Parliament
Secretariat seeking the vote of confidence in the 205-seat lower
house of parliament during the session, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The winter session, the 11th since the country reintroduced the
multi-party parliamentary system in 1990, will also discuss and
approve some important bills including those on decentralization
and local autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
