<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Financial Targets Largely Met (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government largely met
its financial macro-control targets last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, show that China's supply of the narrow money (M1), cash plus
enterprises' demand deposits, went up by 18.9 percent in 1996 to
reach 2.85 trillion yuan by year-end.
</P>
<P>
Supply of the broad money (M2), cash plus all sorts of
deposits, grew by 25.3 percent last year to more than 7.6 trillion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The growth rates of the two indices are very close to the
targets set by the government at the beginning of 1996, which were
18 percent and 25 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's cash supply went up by 11.6 percent to 91.7 billion
yuan last year, well below the 100 billion yuan limit imposed by
the State Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Freight Train Service To Hong Kong, Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Inland parts of China are
trying to shorten the amount of time goods take to reach Hong Kong
and Macao and to make sure that the three express-trains now
available provide fresh or frozen foods and livestock of top
quality more timely.
</P>
<P>
An executive with the Henan Provincial Cereals, Oils and
Foodstuffs Import and Export Corporation disclosed in an interview
with Xinhua that an effort is also being made to make arrival
times in Hong Kong or Macao more reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Following a principle of "good quality, proper quantity,
balanced supply, and promptness", railway departments have
acquired 6,000 new pieces of equipment for livestocks or cold
storage, and have built more service stops en route that provide
water, ice, and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The three express freight trains started service in 1962, from
Shanghai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, and Changsha, with the support of
Premier Zhou Enlai, to meet the fresh food needs of Hong Kong and
Macao compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The service has never been shut down, even during the Cultural
Revolution, or in periods of heavy traffic, flooding, bridge
collapses, or landslides.
</P>
<P>
The three trains have carried more than 80 million live pigs,
five million head of cattle, and a large amount of poultry, eggs,
fresh fish, vegetables, fruits, and frozen food in the past 35
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0240 </DOCNO>
