<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for Restoring Calm in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini today called on all Albanian parties to "sit around a table"
and seek to restore calm in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first thing to do is to restore calm in Albania and "all
(Albanian) parties must sit around a table," Dini said on the
sidelines of a trade fair.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the law and order problem in Albania where the
government has resigned and street violence remained unabated, the
Italian foreign minister said, "We cannot maintain law and
order ... this is something (the Albanian) authorities must do."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Albanian authorities to establish dialogue and not
resort to confrontation and violence.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that the unstable situation in Albania has become a
problem for all of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see intervention by Europe and international
financial organizations," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
The two months of protests, which were sparked by the collapse
of popular pyramid investment schemes, showed no signs of ebbing
despite the resignation on Saturday of the government led by Prime
Minister Aleksander Meksi.
</P>
<P>
Violence broke out in several cities across the country after
the parliament declared a state of emergency Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that four people have been killed by stray bullets
since street violence broke out.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha has threatened to quash the
unrest. 
