<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China City To Push Leading Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Chengdu, the capital of southwest
China's Sichuan province, intends to turn electronics, machinery,
foodstuff, and pharmaceuticals into leading industries locally by
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The city had more than 109 billion yuan in industrial output
value in 1996, and an annual growth rate of more than 25 percent
in recent years. In the 1996-2000 period, the city plans to invest
nearly 24 billion yuan in developing the four industries into
local pillar sectors.
</P>
<P>
During that period it also aims to help expand 66 large
enterprises with annual output value exceeding 500 million yuan
each, five of which are expected to have more than five billion
yuan in output value.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city will give priority to 14 hi-tech and
popular categories of products, such as optical fibre and cable
and engineering machinery to add local name-brand products.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output value of the four leading sectors is expected
to account for more than 70 percent of the local total by the turn
of the century, with the annual growth rate expected to reach 20
percent by then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
