<HEADLINE> No Govt Officials to Have Medical Treatment Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has abolished the existing provision of medical treatment
abroad for government officials at public expense.
</P>
<P>
All the concerned departments have been directed for strict
compliance and immediate implementation of this decision, which is
one of the measures taken by Sharif to curtail the non-development
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"No exceptions are to be made in this regard, such requests
will not be processed either by the Ministry of Health, Government
of Pakistan or by the provincial health departments," Sharif said
Sunday in a directive.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that in most of the cases the provision of
medical treatment abroad at public expense has been exercised by
the senior officials of the state and public representatives in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, they used to avail this facility for minor ailment and
diseases which could have been easily treated in the country. Due
to this provision, millions of dollars were being wasted annually
and it was an economic burden on the national exchequer.
</P>
