<HEADLINE> Thai State Universities to Have Electronic Libraries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 3 (Xinhua) -- All state universities in Thailand
will have electronic libraries within three years, according to
the Thai University Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Between 1998 and 2000, the ministry will spend one billion baht
(40 million U.S. dollars) to upgrade libraries at state-run
universities, Wanchai Sirichana, permanent secretary for the
ministry, was quoted today by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
This will involve linking state-run universities through
computer networks to give students nationwide equal access to
information from books, research papers and other materials
available worldwide, Wanchai said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it will help cut the operating cost of libraries,
which have to spend a sizable sum buying new books and mending old
ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Suebsaeng Promboon, a member of the
House Committee on Education, has called on the University Affairs
Ministry to install a fiber optic cable network nationwide so that
people can have a ready access to electronic libraries.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry should also establish a fund to buy
personal computers for students and teachers, push the government
to cut taxes on educational computer software and make Internet
services available in libraries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
