<HEADLINE> Albania Declares State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian People's Assembly
(parliament) Sunday declared a state of emergency throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The assembly, responding to two months of violence in the
country, approved an "emergency act" in an afternoon session and
voted unanimously to declare a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The measure was taken after the Constitutional and public order
had been seriously violated, the assembly said.
</P>
<P>
It also decided not to adjourn until the law and order is
restored and to merge the Interior Ministry and the National
Intelligence Bureau to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
Before the assembly approved the act, Albanian President Sali
Berisha threatened to use every means provided by law to handle
the situation.
</P>
<P>
The two months of protests, which were sparked by the collapse
of popular pyramid investment schemes, showed no signs of ebbing
despite the resignation on Saturday of the government led by Prime
Minister Aleksander Meksi.
</P>
<P>
Violence broke out in several cities across the country after
the parliament declared a state of emergency Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that at least four people have been killed by
stray bullets since street violence broke out. 
</P>
