<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Industry in China to See Turning Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's auto industry is
approaching a turning point as more individuals are buying motor
vehicles, today's "China Daily" quoted a senior offical from the
Ministry of Machine-building Industry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vice-minister Lu Fuyan predicted that when 51 percent of the
automobiles are sold to individuals and institutional purchases no
longer dominate the automotive market, the industry will see the
real turning point.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, 34 percent of China's three million
passenger cars, buses and trucks and at least 95 percent of the 17
million motorcycles and 4.7 million farm vehicles sold were bought
by individuals.
</P>
<P>
By 1995, 2.5 million, or 24 percent of the 10.5 million
passenger cars, trucks and buses were owned privately, compared
with 19 percent of 8.2 million in 1993, 15 percent of 5.5 million
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
At the largest automotive market in the country's capital of
Beijing --the Beijing Asian Games Village Automobile Exchange-- 59
percent of the motor vehicles sold last year were bought privately.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that existing regional rules restricting the use of
private vehicles and discrimination against economy cars, as well
as exorbitant taxes and fees levied on car owners will not prevent
demand from rising.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the production and sale of motorcycles have grown
steadily. In 1996, the country churned out 9.3 million units,
compared with 7.8 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that there is a bright side this year as sales of all
types of motor vehicles have risen, heralding a good year for
auto-makers and companies selling cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Quality of Industrial Products Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The quality of Chinese
industrial products has maintained a steady rise over the past
decade, with the "first-grade" and "high-quality" products in
particular expanding their shares among the country's industrial
output, according to the newly released results of a nationwide
industrial survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, of 770 kinds of major industrial products, says
that in terms of output value about 19.8 percent of the country's
qualified products met the benchmark standards for "high-quality"
goods in 1995, enjoying the same quality assurance as advanced
foreign products. Meanwhile, 41.5 percent reached the standard of
"first-grade" products, which stands for the average level of
industrial goods on global markets.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of "high-quality" and "first-grade" goods
represents increases of 3.5 percentage points and 16 percentage
points, respectively, from a decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
The survey report, however, showed that a quality gap still
remains between domestic products and those of advanced nations,
so Chinese enterprises should make more efforts for quality
improvement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
