<HEADLINE> Philippines Seeks to Lower Trade Gap With 5 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines hopes to reduce its
trade deficit with five South Asia and Middle East countries
during President Ramos' ongoing visit to these countries, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista was quoted as
saying that several business groups have joined the president's
delegation, which is now in India, and will go to Bangladesh,
Pakistan, Qatar and Bahrain later in search of potential export
opportunities and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Among the investment areas they are looking at in these
countries are construction, port development, computer software
and consumer goods, Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
For potential exports, the department has identified
leathercraft, cocochemicals, processed food and electronic
microcircuits, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bautista admitted the Philippines has a trade deficit of 70
million U.S. dollars with India, 9.8 million dollars with
Bangladesh, 59 million dollars with Pakistan, 42 million dollars
with Qatar, and 15.5 million dollars with Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Although the Philippines would continue to have a trade gap
with Bahrain and Qatar due to the country's oil dependency,
Bautista said it could narrow the trade deficit with India,
Pakistan and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
India's top exports to the Philippines include rice,
pharmaceutical products, beef and steel products. Bangladesh
exports jute bags and some construction materials while Pakistan
provides cotton, leather and fabrics.  
</P>
