<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Education (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of illiterates among
the people aged 15 to 47 in China were reduced by four million
last year.
</P>
<P>
Now only six percent of the Chinese population are
illiterates, while the figure during the first half of the
century was 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Central and local fiscal expenditures for education last
year reached 104.022 billion yuan, 4.6 percent more than the
budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
State Education Commission claimed that last year 10 billion
yuan was invested in housing for teachers across the country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, 50 percent of counties in China had
basically adopted the 9-year compulsory education, and some 190
million more people had had access to such education.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's over 1,000 universities and colleges
recruited 966,000 freshmen, and 1.37 million students entered
vocational and technical secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
In total, the number of students in institutions of higher
learning for adults reached 2.656 million, and students in
vocational and technical secondary schools amounted to 3.1
million.
</P>
<P>
Among all high school students, 56.8 percent study in
vocational schools, and the number of various vocational
training institutions has exceeded 400,000.
</P>
<P>
As a sign for the deepening of education reform, over 64
percent of China's colleges and universities last year started
to charge tuition fees on their students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
