<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Basic Education (15) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 190 million more Chinese
people had access to nine-year compulsory education in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission said that 457 more counties,
cities and districts across China largely made nine-year
compulsory education universal and wiped out illiteracy among
people aged between 15 and 47 last year, bringing to over 1,480
the total number of such counties, cities and districts.
</P>
<P>
An SEC official said that the first phase of making nine-year
compulsory education universal and eliminating illiteracy among
people aged 15 to 47 has concluded with success.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has decided to make nine-year compulsory
education universal and wipe out illiteracy across the country by
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the illiteracy rate among people of
the 15-47 age group is six percent.
</P>
<P>
Nine out of every ten Chinese could not read or write in 1949
when New China was founded. Overall, China's illiteracy rate is
12.1 percent at present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
