<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Sign WTO Infotech Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
agreed in principle to sign a World Trade Organization (WTO)
agreement that will eliminate or reduce import duties on
information technology products, Local newspaper The Manila Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista
as saying the government has agreed to sign the WTO's Information
Technology Agreement (ITA) after concerned local firms dropped
their opposition to the proposed accord.
</P>
<P>
The opposition of some local companies, many of whom make
infotech products themselves, had earlier prompted the government
to put on hold its endorsement of the ITA, a WTO initiative that
is being pushed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Prevailing tariffs on infotech products range from 3 to 20
percent, but Bautista said most computer products are subject to
import duties of only between 3 and 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The elimination or reduction of import duties on infotech
products is expected to boost further the computerization of
Philippine businesses as well as households, he said.
</P>
<P>
In getting the support of affected local firms, the government
decided to adopt a two-stage plan in reducing tariffs on
information technology products, Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the first stage, which will take effect in the
year 2000, entails the removal of tariffs on "non-sensitive"
computer products. The second stage entails the removal of tariffs
on "sensitive products" by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the private sector has also agreed to expand the
list of non-sensitive products, but he did not give an exact
number. The Department of Trade and Industry earlier received a
proposal to limit to only 60 the number of items in government's
list of non-sensitive products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
