<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- All the leading newspapers in
China today frontpaged the story that Deng Xiaoping's ashes were
scattered at sea yesterday in accordance with the wishes of Deng
and his family. Deng, who passed away in Beijing on February 19 at
the age of 93, was cremated on February 24.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A lengthy report with five accompanying pictures reported
the whole process of casting Deng Xiaoping's ashes into sea.
</P>
<P>
-- Second plenary meeting of the fifth session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) was held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of State Planning Commission,
reported planning on national economy and social development and
Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli delivered a report on the central
and local budgets.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng called for accelerating efforts to translate
scientific and technological achievements into productive forces
Sunday when he joined a discussion of CPPCC (Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference) deputies from scientific and
technological circles.
</P>
<P>
-- Chairman of CPPCC National Committee Li Ruihuan asked CPPCC
deputies from central and local governments to cherish the
situation of unity and stability and work to solve problems.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-premier Zhu Rongji told CPPCC deputies from economic
circle to open their mind and take a bolder step in finding a way
for further development.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin called for accelerating the
development in central and western China Saturday when he joined
the discussion of legislators from Northwest China's Gansu
Province and Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
-- State Planning Commission Minister Chen Jinhua Sunday
unveiled China's economic blue-print for 1997, which is aimed at a
moderate yet stable pace of development amid challenges of
restructuring industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
-- The government will continue to implement moderately tight
fiscal policies this year. It will fight to cut fiscal deficits
but will guarantee the financing of key expenditure sectors,
Minister of Finance Liu Zhongli said Sunday. 
</P>
