<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Deficit Down (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government attained
the goal of controlling deficit last year.
</P>
<P>
China's deficit was 61 billion yuan in 1996, 442 million yuan
less than the budgeted figure. Its 1995 deficit was 66.442 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has vowed to eradicate fiscal deficit by
the end of this century. After years of expansion, China's deficit
has declined in recent years, though not as fast as expected.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister of finance said that deficit in 1997 is
planned at 57 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Treasury Bonds (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's treasury bond issue
reached a record amount in 1996, to the tune of 196.742 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The amount was 1.485 billion yuan more than the budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
China resumed the issue of government bonds in 1985 and annual
issue has been expanding rapidly over the past years, due to a
1995 legal stipulation that the state treasury can no longer cover
fiscal deficits with overdrafts from the central bank and to a
growing need to repay the principal and interest of old bonds.
</P>
<P>
More than 153 billion yuan in treasury bonds was issued in
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
