<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Agriculture (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's agriculture developed
steadily last year, with grain output hitting a record high.
</P>
<P>
The country produced 480 billion kg of grain in 1996, an
increase of more than 13.4 billion kg over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Due to an oversupply and bad weather, China's output of
oil-bearing crops was down by 500,000 tons to 22 million tons last
year, which was still the second largest in history.
</P>
<P>
Cotton production declined by 570,000 tons to 4.2 million tons.
There was a drop of close to 10 million mu (about 666,000 ha) in
acreage sown to cotton.
</P>
<P>
The output of meat and aquatic products reached 58 million tons
and 28 million tons, respectively, last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Income for Rural Residents (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The per capita net income of
China's rural residents hit a record high of 1,900 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an increase of nine percent in real terms
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the income came from agricultural
production; and the part out of industry and the service sector
also grew steadily in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Income increases in the rural areas of west China, which lagged
behind the east in terms of economic development in recent years,
approached or reached the country's average.
</P>
<P>
The per capita net income of urban Chinese was up 3.3 percent
in real terms to 4,377 yuan last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Gross Domestic Product (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's domestic gross product
grew 9.7 percent to 6,779.5 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase rate, which follows years of two-digit growth, was
very close to the central government's target of some 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
China has made it an economic macro-control target to keep
inflation rise below economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China's inflation measured by the retail price index, which
excludes the cost of services, grew 6.1 percent in 1996, well blow
the planned limit of around 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
