<DOCNO> XIE19970303.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McRae Leads Leg Two Safari Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Briton Colin McRae leads the
Safari Rally with their Subaru Impreza car after two days and 960
kilometers of competitive sections.
</P>
<P>
The Safari Rally is the third round of world championship. In
Sunday's competitions, Richard Burns of Britain in a Mitsubishi
was only seven minutes behind McRae and Kenyan Ian Duncan was
less than two minutes behind Burns. The two is fighting a close
battle for the second place.
</P>
<P>
McRae had a rear suspension damage during last section, but
managed to keep his leading place.
</P>
<P>
McRae "is using his head, driving really steadily, no
heroics," said McRae's co-driver Nicky Grist.
</P>
<P>
Overnight leader German Armin Schwarz, finished fourth after
some mechanic troubles on his Ford Escort car.
</P>
<P>
Today's run through the rocky regions north of Nairobi, has
been less punishing on the survivors of the first leg on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, Finn driver Tommi Makinen, 1996's world champion and
Safari winner, retired today as his Mitsubishi car had three
punctures on today's first competitive section.
</P>
<P>
Makinen's car motored on a flat and with transmission troubles
for about 40 kilometers but finally quit 23 kilometers before the
Elburgon control.
</P>
<P>
McRae had an oil leak from his power steering while local
driver Ian Duncan's front struts are still faulty this morning.
</P>
<P>
He went crashing through a wall of rocks placed on the road
near the end of the second competitive section of the day, but
escaped with minor damage to his Subaru.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the rally, regarded widely as the toughest event
on world championships calendar, has changed at least four times
in a dramatic start to the second day of the event.
</P>
<P>
Richard Burns, second overnight and with his Mitsubishi's
clutch no more serviceable, had to come to a near standstill
several times in the dusty wake of Schwarz's limping Ford car
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Burns also dropped crucial minutes with a "clumsy" puncture
change on today's third section.
</P>
<P>
"The car fell off the jack and we were less than brilliant,"
said Burns' navigator Robert Reld.
</P>
<P>
Schwarz and his navigator Denis Giraudet lost nearly half an
hour and the lead with a mid-section repair by themselves to a
broken rear shock-absorber.
</P>
<P>
World championship leader Spaniard Carlos Sainz and Swedish
Kenneth Eriksson, the winner of the latest round in Sweden, were
forced out of rally on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
So far at least 39 entrants have quit the rally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
