<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures for 1996: Foreign Exchange Reserves (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 3 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange reserves
grew by 31.5 billion US dollars in 1996, the largest annual
increase, to 105 billion US dollars by year end.
</P>
<P>
The current amount is second only to Japan's.
</P>
<P>
After the Chinese government overhauled the country's foreign
exchange system by unifying the yuan's dual exchange rates against
hard currencies on January 1, 1994, the country's hard currency
reserves have expanded rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign exchange reserves surged from 21.2 billion US
dollars at the end of 1993 to 73.56 billion US dollars at the end
of 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
