<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Wins Philadelphia Tennis Champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Top seed and world No. 1 Pete
Sampras beat unseeded Patrick Rafter of Australia 5-7, 7-6 (7-4),
6-3 in the finals of the 589,250-U.S.-dollar Advanta
Championships held in Philadelphia today.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who earned 110,000 dollars, extended his winning
streak to 20 matches and grabbed his 11th title in his last 18
tournaments including the Australian Open in January.
</P>
<P>
He picked up his third singles title of 1997, his third title
at this event and the 47th of his career. He captured the
Australian Open in January and won last month's Sybase Open in
San Jose, California.
</P>
<P>
Sampras served poorly, getting his first serve in play just 55
percent of the time. He was broken by Rafter for three times.
</P>
<P>
He was broken in the third game of the opening set. However,
he broke back in the 10th game as Rafter hit a forehand return
out.
</P>
<P>
The Australian, playing in his first final since Hong Kong in
1994, sprinted around the court, challenging Sampras' approach
shots and volleys, then broke back in the next game and held on
for the set.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, Sampras fired an ace to take a 5-4 lead.
Rafter hit a passing shot wide for set point and backhanded a
volley into the net to take the match into the deciding set.
</P>
<P>
Rafter went up a break in the third set, but Sampras broke
back in the next game on a winning overhead smash. Sampras broke
again in the seventh game as Rafter hit a forehand volley into
the net. Sampras concluded the two-hour, 20-minute match with a
forehand, crosscourt winner.
</P>
<P>
Sampras has now won four of five career meetings with Rafter
and improved to 16-0 lifetime in finals against players ranked
outside the top 20. Rafter is currently ranked 60th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, 24, was making his first appearance in an ATP Tour
singles final in three years. He prevailed in Manchester in 1994
for his lone career singles title and also reached the finals in
Hong Kong earlier that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
