<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Meet Opposition to Reduce Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Islamist Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan said today that he would meet opposition
leaders in a bid to reduce the current political tension in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters prior to a meeting of his Welfare
Party's central executive board, Erbakan said Turkey was really
in need of a relaxed and peaceful environment.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would start a round of discussions with
opposition leaders to explore means for achieving such an aim.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made this announcement as local media said that the
coalition government would receive some important recommendations
from the National Security Council (NSC) Monday.
</P>
<P>
These points from the NSC meeting, which was held Friday, were
reportedly aimed at underscoring a total commitment to the
secular system established by Kemel Ataturk, founder of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Severely warned by the NSC to safegauard Turkish secularism,
Erbakan said he would hold his first meeting Monday with leaders
of the Democratic Left Party Bulent Ecevit, one of his harshest
critics.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the main one of the NSC
recommendations was a suggestion of reviving article 163 of
the Turkish Penal Code, which bans politically motivated religious
activities, especially those that endangered the country's
secular system.
</P>
<P>
The Welfare Party's recent proposals on ordering women civil
servants to wear Islamic-style head covering in government
offices and building a mosque in one of Istanbul's main
commercial squares triggered strong criticism from the secular
forces in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a Muslim nation which has a secular system.
</P>
</TEXT>
